\end_layout

\end_inset

To secure personal advancement,
 it is much more profito able to be eloquent,
 than to be wise and grave in council.
 
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 -London Daily Telegraph.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CHAPTER I
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
DEVELOPING COURAGE AND SELFCONFIDENCE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More than eighteen thousand business men,
 since 1912,
 have been members of the various public speaking courses conducted by the author.
 Most of them have,
 at his request,
 written stating why they had enrolled for this training and what they hoped to obtain from it.
 Naturally,
 the phraseology varied;
 but the central desire in these letters,
 the basic want in the vast majority,
 remained surprisingly the same:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

When I am called upon to stand up and speak,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 man after man wrote,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I become so self-conscious,
 so frightened,
 that I can't think clearly,
 can't concentrate,
 can't remember what I had intended to say.
 I want to gain selfconfidence,
 poise,
 and the ability to think on my feet.
 I want to get my thoughts together in logical order and I want to be able to say my say clearly and convincingly before a business group or audience.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thousands of their confessions sounded about like that.
 To cite a concrete case:
 Years ago,
 a gentleman here called Mr.
 D.
 W.
 Ghent,
 joined my public speaking course in Philadelphia.
 Shortly after the opening session,
 he invited me to lunch with him in the Manufacturers' Club.
 He was a
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 man of middle age and had always led an active life;
 was head of his own manufacturing establishment,
 a leader in church work and civic activities.
 While we were having lunch that day,
 he leaned across the table and said:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I have been asked many times to talk before various gatherings,
 but I have never been able to do so.
 I get so fussed,
 my mind becomes an utter blank:
 so I have sidestepped it all my life.
 But I am chairman now of a board of college trustees.
 I must preside at their meetings.
 I simply have to do some talking.
 .
 .
 .
 Do you think it will be possible for me to learn to speak at this late date in my life?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Do I think,
 Mr.
 Ghent?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 I replied.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

It is not a question of my thinking.
 I know you can,
 and I know you will if you will only practise and follow the directions and instructions.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He wanted to believe that,
 but it seemed too rosy,
 too optimistic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I am afraid you are just being kind,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 he answered,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

that you are merely trying to encourage me.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After he had completed his training,
 we lost touch with each other for a while.
 In 1921,
 we met and lunched together again at the Manufacturers' Club.
 We sat in the same corner and occupied the same table that we had had on the first occasion.
 Re.
 minding him of our former conversation,
 I asked him if I had been too sanguine then.
 He took a little red-backed note book out of his pocket and showed me a list of talks and dates for which he was booked.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

And the ability to make these,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 he confessed,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

the pleasure I get in doing it,
 the addi-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 tional service I can render to the communitythese are among the most gratifying things in my life.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The International Conference for the Limitation of Armaments had been held in Washington shortly before that.
 When it was known that Lloyd George was planning to attend it,
 the Baptists of Philadelphia cabled,
 inviting him to speak at a great mass meeting to be held in their city.
 Lloyd George cabled back that,
 if he came to Washington,
 he would accept their invitation.
 And Mr.
 Ghent informed me that he himself had been chosen,
 from among all the Baptists of that city,
 to introduce England's premier to the audience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And this was the man who had sat at that same table less than three years before and solemnly asked me if I thought he would ever be able to talk in public!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Was the rapidity with which he forged ahead in his speaking ability unusual?
 Not at all.
 There have been hundreds of similar cases.
 For example-to quote one more specific instance-years ago,
 a Brooklyn physician,
 whom we will call Dr.
 Curtis,
 spent the winter in Florida near the training grounds of the Giants.
 Being an enthusiastic baseball fan,
 he often went to see them practise.
 In time,
 he became quite friendly with the team,
 and was invited to attend a banquet given in their honor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the coffee and nuts were served,
 several prominent guests were called upon to 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

say a few words.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suddenly,
 with the abruptness and unex pectedness of an explosion,
 he heard the toastmaster remark:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

We have a physician with us to-night,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 and I am going to ask Dr.
 Curtis to talk on a Baseball Player's Health.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Was he prepared?
 Of course.
 He had had the best preparation in the world:
 he had been studying hygiene and practising medicine for almost a third of a century.
 He could have sat in his chair and talked about this subject all night to the man seated on his right or left.
 But to get up and say the same things to even a small audience-that was another matter.
 That was a paralyzing matter.
 His heart doubled its pace and skipped beats at the very contemplation of it.
 He had never made a public speech in his life,
 and every thought that he had had now took wings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What was he to do?
 The audience was applauding.
 Every one was looking at him.
 He shook his head.
 But that served only to heighten the applause,
 to increase the demand.
 The cries of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Dr.
 Curtis!
 Speech!
 Speech!
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 grew louder and more insistent.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 He was in positive misery.
 He knew that if he got up he would fail,
 that he would be unable to utter half a dozen sentences.
 So he arose,
 and,
 without saying a word,
 turned his back on his friends and walked silently out of the room,
 a deeply embarrassed and humiliated man.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Small wonder that one of the first things he did after getting back to Brooklyn was to come to the Central Y.
 M.
 C.
 A.
 and enroll in the course in Public Speaking.
 He didn't propose to be put to the blush and be stricken dumb a second time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He was the kind of student that delights an in.
 structor:
 he was in dead earnest.
 He wanted to be
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 able to talk,
 and there was no half-heartedness about his desires.
 He prepared his talks thoroughly,
 he practised them with a will,
 and he never missed a single session of the course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He did precisely what such a student always does:
 he progressed at a rate that surprised him,
 that surpassed his fondest hopes.
 After the first few sessions his nervousness subsided,
 his confidence mounted higher and higher.
 In two months he had become the star speaker of the group.
 He was soon accepting invitations to speak elsewhere;
 he now loved the feel and exhilaration of it,
 the distinction and the additional friends it brought him.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A member of the New York City Republican Campaign Committee,
 hearing one of his public addresses,
 invited Dr.
 Curtis to stump the city for his party.
 How surprised that politician would have been had he realized that,
 only a year before,
 the speaker had gotten up and left a public banquet hall in shame and confusion because he was tonguetied with audience-fear!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The gaining of self-confidence and courage,
 and the ability to think calmly and clearly while talking to a group is not one-tenth as difficult as most men imagine.
 It is not a gift bestowed by Providence on only a few rarely endowed individuals.
 It is like the ability to play golf.
 Any man can develop his own latent capacity if he has sufficient desire to do so.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is there the faintest shadow of a reason why you should not be able to think as well in a perpendicular position before an audience as you can when sitting down?
 Surely,
 you know there is not.
 In fact,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 you ought to think better when facing a group of men.
 Their presence ought to stir you and lift you.
 A great many speakers will tell you that the presence of an audience is a stimulus,
 an inspiration,
 that drives their brains to function more clearly,
 more keenly.
 At such times,
 thoughts,
 facts,
 ideas,
 that they did not know they possessed,
 drift smoking by,
 as Henry Ward Beecher said;
 and they have but to reach out and lay their hands hot upon them.
 That ought to be your experience.
 It probably will be if you practise and persevere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of this much,
 however,
 you may be absolutely sure:
 training and practise will wear away your audience-fright and give you self-confidence and an abiding courage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do not imagine that your case is unusually diffi,
 cult.
 Even those who afterwards became the most eloquent representatives of their generation were,
 at the outset of their careers,
 afflicted by this blinding fear and self-consciousness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
William Jennings Bryan,
 battle-marked veteran that he was,
 admitted that,
 in his first attempts,
 his knees fairly smote together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mark Twain,
 the first time he stood up to lecture,
 felt as if his mouth were filled with cotton and his pulse were speeding for some prize cup.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Grant took Vicksburg and led to victory one of the greatest armies the world had ever seen up to that time;
 yet,
 when he attempted to speak in public,
 he admitted he had something very like locomotor ataxia.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The late Jean Jaurès,
 the most powerful political speaker that France produced during his genera-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 tion,
 sat,
 for a year,
 tongue-tied in the Chamber of Deputies before he could summon up the courage to make his initial speech.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The first time I attempted to make a public talk,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 confessed Lloyd George,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I tell you I was in a state of misery.
 It is no figure of speech,
 but literally true,
 that my tongue clove to the roof of my mouth;
 and,
 at first,
 I could hardly get out a word.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
John Bright,
 the illustrious Englishman,
 who,
 during the civil war,
 defended in England the cause of union and emancipation,
 made his maiden speech before a group of country folk gathered in a school building.
 He was so frightened on the way to the place,
 so fearful that he would fail,
 that he implored his companion to start applause to bolster him up whenever he showed signs of giving way to his nervousness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Charles Stewart Parnell,
 the great Irish leader,
 at the outset of his speaking career,
 was so nervous,
 according to the testimony of his brother,
 that he frequently clenched his fists until his nails sank into his flesh and his palms bled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Disraeli admitted that he would rather have led a cavalry charge than to have faced the House of Commons for the first time.
 His opening speech there was a ghastly failure.
 So was Sheridan's.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact,
 so many of the famous speakers of England have made poor showings at first that there is now a feeling in Parliament that it is rather an inauspicious omen for a young man's initial talk to be a decided success.
 So take heart.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After watching the careers and aiding somewhat in the development of so many speakers,
 the author is always glad when a student has,
 at the outset,
 a certain amount of flutter and nervous agitation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a certain responsibility in making a talk,
 even if it is to only two dozen men in a business conference-a certain strain,
 a certain shock,
 a certain excitement.
 The speaker ought to be keyed up like a thoroughbred straining at the bit.
 The immortal Cicero said,
 two thousand years ago,
 that all public speaking of real merit was characterized by nervousness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Speakers often experience this same feeling even when they are talking over the radio.
 
