\begin_layout Standard
The first syllable of finance-both verb and nourn -may be pronounced 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{in}$
\end_inset

 ( 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as in 
\begin_inset Formula $it$
\end_inset

 ),
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f\bar{i}$
\end_inset

 ( 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as in ice);
 but remember that the accent must go on the last syllable.
 This word is commonly mispronounced.
 Watch it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first syllable of predecessor may be préd ( 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 as in met),
 or pré ( 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 as in eel);
 but the third,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 not the first,
 syllable must be accented-predeCESSor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can you pronounce correctly the italicized words in the following sentences?
 If in doubt,
 see Chapter I.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I.
 In his address,
 the expert agriculturist made no pretense whatever to having done any original research.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2.
 Do adults read the romances appearing in the magazines?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3.
 He protested that we would not detour.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4.
 He said in a robust voice that he would contest the decision as a matter of routine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
ERRORS IN ENGLISH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Review.
 For the purposes of review,
 a paragraph or so will head this section of each chapter.
 A number of mistakes previously discussed will be given.
 Finding them will be an interesting game and,
 at the same time,
 will increase your ability to detect errors and to profit by them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are four errors in the following paragraph:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I am determined that I shall go,
 even though it shall cause the heavens to fall and will bring unhappiness to all concerned.
 So leave me do it,
 whatever can come.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New Study Material.
 The English language is burdened with a number of verbs which cause trouble.
 A thorough understanding of their definitions and of their principal parts will soon cause you to use them correctly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider three different sets of verbs in this category.
 They are lay and lie;
 set and sit;
 raise and rise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Lay-Lie
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To lay means to put an object somewhere.
 So,
 you may say:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I am laying the stamps here.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 He lays the book on the table.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I have laid the matter before the board of directors.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 He laid the foundation for an immense fortune.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 To lie means to recline.
 Examples of use are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I am lying down.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I lie down.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 He lay on his bed yesterday.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 They have lain down on the whole proposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition,
 there is another use of lie in the sense of prevarication.
 The principal parts are lie,
 lied,
 lying,
 lied.
 No examples are necessary to show the usage of these verbs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Set-Sit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To set means to put something somewhere,
 or to make some one to sit.
 Of course,
 the latter usage is merely a corollary of the first.
 Examples are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I set it here as I want to use it.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I am setting the medicine on the table.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I set my watch by standard time last night.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I had set the trap before he came.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I set the baby on the bed.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 To sit means to rest,
 as upon a chair with the body bent at the hips,
 or to rest upon the haunches.
 It also means to take or occupy a seat.
 Examples are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I sit to take my meals.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I am sitting down now.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I sat in the ante-room.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I have sat and waited for hours.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Sit here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Raise-Rise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To raise means to move upward,
 to cause to rise,
 to exalt.
 Examples are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I raised the flag.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I am raising the floor.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 He raised his price.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 He has raised a new question.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 To rise means to ascend,
 as a hill;
 to become erect;
 to emerge;
 to revolt;
 etc.
 Examples are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I rise to a point of order.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I am rising to ask a question.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 The river rose last night.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 The price has risen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Antipathy-Dislike.
 Antipathy is instinctive;
 dislike is often acquired.
 You have an antipathy for hoboes;
 you may dislike your landlord.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Authentic-Genuine.
 Authentic suggests possessing authority and being true to the facts;
 genuine means,
 not counterfeit.
 If a Sandwich Islander wrote a book on ice hockey and signed his name to it,
 the treatise would be genuine but probably not authentic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Behavior-Conduct.
 Behavior refers to our mode of acting in the presence of others-it geners ally refers to a specific instance.
 Conduct refers to the general tone of our actions in the more serious aspects of life.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bound-Determine.
 We are bound to do things by outside influences.
 We determine to do a thing by our own decisions.
 You may be bound by law to send your child to school and determined to send him to college.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-CORRECT BREATHING
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The famous singer,
 Jean De Reszke,
 advised,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

carry the necktie high.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us stand up now and obey his admonition,
 not by raising the shoulders,
 but by lifting the chest to its proper position.
 Stand with your weight on the balls of your feet.
 Put your hand on the top of your head.
 Without lifting your heels from the floor,
 try now to shove your hand off your hair.
 Try to do it,
 not with your arm muscles,
 but by standing as tall as pos-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 sible.
 There.
 That is it.
 Fine!
 You are now standing straight,
 abdomen in,
 necktie and chest high,
 the back of your neck against the back of your collar.
 Have you raised your shoulders?
 If so,
 relax,
 drop them.
 You want to carry your chest high,
 not your shoulders.
 Without lowering the chest,
 exhale.
 Hold it high as the last bit of breath escapes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now you are ready to breathe correctly.
 Close your eyes.
 Inhale deeply,
 slowly,
 easily through the nose.
 Try to feel the same sensation that you felt when you were practising diaphragmatic breathing in bed,
 as we suggested in Chapter I.
 Feel the bottom of your lungs expanding,
 expanding,
 expanding,
 pushing out the lower ribs to the side;
 feel the sensation under your arms;
 feel it at the back;
 feel the diaphragm being pushed down and flattening like an inverted paper dish under pressure from above;
 feel the diaphragm expanding as you place your fingers over the soft spot,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

the doll squeak,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 children call it,
 just underneath the breast bone.
 Exhale slowly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 once more.
 Inhale through your nose.
 Let me caution you again:
 do not raise your shoulders,
 and do not try to enlarge your lungs at the top.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With your necktie high,
 breathe in again,
 feeling the expansion in the middle of your body.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I practise deep breathing every day of my life,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 said Madame Schumann-Heink.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Caruso did the same;
 consequently he developed a diaphragm of extraordinary power.
 When students came to him-as they often did-seeking advice about this all-important matter of correct
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 breathing,
 he usually said to them:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Press your fist with all your strength against my relaxed diaphragm.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Then with a quick,
 sharp intake of breath,
 the famous tenor forced his diaphragm down and his body out with such force as to fling off the pressure of the fist.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 the mere knowledge of correct breathing that you are gathering now will avail you naught unless you apply it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So practise it daily as you walk along the street.
 Practise it when you have an odd moment in the office.
 After you have been concentrating on some task for an hour,
 throw open the window and fill your lungs with air.
 This won't be time lost.
 It will be time saved,
 vigor reinforced,
 health strengthened.
 This practise cannot be indulged in too often.
 It will,
 if faithfully followed,
 become a habit.
 You will wonder then that you ever breathed in any other fashion.
 To breathe from the top of the lungs is only half breathing.
 And 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

he who only half breathes,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says a passage from the Sanskrit,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

only half lives.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you follow daily the directions given here,
 you will not only improve your voice but you will find that the chances of your ever contracting tuberculosis will be very slight;
 and the chances of your escaping the winter's supply of colds that attack others,
 will be very good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
