\begin_layout Section*
HOW TO REMEMBER DATES
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dates can best be retained by connecting them with important dates already firmly established in the mind.
 Isn't it far more difficult,
 for example,
 for an American to remember that the Suez Canal was opened in 1869 than to remember that the first ship passed through it four years after the close of the Civil War?
 If an American tried to remember that the first settlement in Australia was made in 1788,
 the date is likely to drop out of his mind like a loose bolt out of a car;
 it is far more likely to stick if he thinks of it in connection with July 4,
 1776,
 and remembers that it occurred twelve years after the Declaration of Independence.
 That is like screwing a nut on the loose bolt.
 It holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is well to bear this principle in mind when you are selecting a telephone number.
 For example,
 the writer's phone number,
 during the war,
 was 1776.
 No one had difficulty in remembering it.
 If you can secure from the phone company some such number as 1492,
 1861,
 1865,
 1914,
 1918,
 your friends will not have to consult the directory.
 They might forget that your phone number was 1492,
 if you gave them the information in a colorless fashion;
 but would it slip their minds if you said,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

You can easily remember my phone number;
 1492,
 the year Columbus discovered America.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Australians,
 New Zealanders,
 and Canadians who are reading these lines would,
 of course,
 substitute for 1776,
 1861,
 1865 significant dates in their own history.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the best way to memorize the following dates?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 a.
 1564-Birth of Shakespeare.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 b.
 1607-The first English settlement in Amereica was made in Jamestown.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 c.
 1819-The birth of Queen Victoria.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 d.
 1807-The birth of Robert E.
 Lee.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 e.
 1789-The Bastile was destroyed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You would doubtlessly find it tiresome to memorize,
 by sheer mechanical repetition,
 the names of the thirteen original states in the order in which they entered the Union.
 But tie them together with a story and the memorizing can be done with a fraction of the time and trying.
 Read the following paragraph just once.
 Concentrate.
 When you have finished,
 see if you cannot name the thirteen states in their correct order:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One Saturday afternoon a young lady from Delaware bought a ticket over the Pennsylvania railroad for a little outing.
 She packed a New Jersey sweater in her suitcase,
 and visited a friend,
 Georgia,
 in Connecticut.
 The next morning the hostess and her visitor attended Mass in a church on Mary's land.
 Then they took the South car.
 line home,
 and dined on a new ham,
 which had been roasted by Virginia,
 the colored cook,
 from New York.
 After dinner they took the North car line and rode to the island.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
HOW TO REMEMBER THE POINTS OF YOUR TALK
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are only two ways by which we can possibly think of a thing:
 first,
 by means of an outside stimulus;
 second,
 by association with something
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 already in the mind.
 Applied to speeches,
 that means just this:
 first,
 you can recall your points by the aid of some outside stimulus such as notesbut who likes to see a speaker use notes?
 Second,
 you can remember your points by associating them with something already in the mind.
 They should be arranged in such a logical order that the first one leads inevitably to the second,
 and the second to the third as naturally as the door of one room leads into another.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That sounds simple,
 but it may not prove so for the beginner whose thinking powers are rendered hors de combat with fear.
 There is,
 however,
 a method of tying your points together that is easy,
 rapid,
 and all but fool-proof.
 I refer to the use of a nonsense sentence.
 To illustrate:
 suppose you wish to discuss a veritable jumble of ideas,
 unassociated and hence hard to remember,
 such as,
 for example,
 cow,
 cigar,
 Napoleon,
 house,
 religion.
 Let us see if we cannot weld those ideas like the links of a chain by means of this absurd sentence:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The cow smoked a cigar and hooked Napoleon,
 and the house burned down with religion.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 will you please cover the above sentence with your hand while you answer these questions?
 What is the third point in that talk;
 the fifth;
 fourth;
 second;
 first?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Does the method work?
 It does!
 And the members of this course are urged to use it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any group of ideas can be linked together in some such fashion,
 and the more ridiculous the sentence used for the linking,
 the easier it will be to recall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
WHAT TO DO IN CASE OF A COMPLETE BREAKDOWN
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us suppose that,
 in spite of all his preparation and precaution,
 a speaker,
 in the middle of his talk,
 suddenly finds his mind a blank-suddenly finds himself staring at his hearers completely balked,
 unable to go on-a terrifying situation.
 His pride rebels at sitting down in confusion and defeat.
 He feels that he might be able to think of his next point,
 of some point,
 if he had only ten,
 fifteen seconds of grace;
 but even fifteen seconds of frantic silence before an audience would be little less than disastrous.
 What is to be done?
 When a certain well known U.
 S.
 Senator recently found himself in this situation he asked his audience if he were speaking loudly enough,
 if he could be heard distinctly in the back of the room.
 He knew that he was He was not seeking information.
 He was seeking time.
 And in that momentary pause,
 he grasped his thought and proceeded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But perhaps the best life-saver in such a mental hurricane is this:
 use the last word,
 or phrase,
 or idea in your last sentence for the beginning of a new sentence.
 This will make an endless chain that,
 like Tennyson's brook and,
 I regret to say,
 with as little purpose as Tennyson's brook,
 will run on forever.
 Let us see how it works in practise.
 Let us imagine that a speaker,
 talking on Business Success,
 finds himself in a blind mental alley after having said:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The average employe does not get ahead because he takes so little real interest in his work;
 displavs so little initiative.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Initiative.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Start a sentence with 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

initiative.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 You will probably have no idea of what you are going to say or how you are going to end the sentence,
 but,
 nevertheless,
 begin.
 Even a poor showing is more to be desired than utter defeat.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Initiative means originality,
 doing a thing on your own,
 without eternally waiting to be told.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is not a scintillating observation.
 It won't make speech history.
 But isn't it better than an agonizing silence?
 Our last phrase was what?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

waiting to be told.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 All right,
 let us start a new sentence with that idea.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The constant telling and guiding and driving of employees who refuse to do any original thinking is one of the most exasperating things imaginable.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Well,
 we got through that one.
 Let us plunge again.
 This time we must say something about imagination:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Imagination-that is what is needed.
 Vision.
 'Where there is no vision,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Solomon said,
 'the people perish.' 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We did two that time without a hitch.
 Let us take heart and continue:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The number of employees who perish each year in the battle of business is really lamentable.
 I say lamentable,
 because with just a little more loyalty,
 a little more ambition,
 a little more enthusiasm,
 these same men and women might have lifted themselves over the line of demarcation between success and failure.
 Yet the failure in business never admits that this is the case.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And so on.
 .
 .
 .
 While the speaker is saying these platitudes off the top of his mind,
 he should,
 at the same time,
 be thinking hard of the next point in his planned speech,
 of the thing he had originally intended to say.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This endless chain method of talking will,
 if continued very long,
 trap the speaker into discussing plum pudding or the price of canary birds.
 However,
 it is a splendid first aid to the injured mind broken down temporarily through forgetfulness:
 and,
 as such,
 it has been the means of resuscitating many a gasping and dying speech.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
WE CANNOT IMPROVE OUR MEMORIES FOR ALL CLASSES OF THINGS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I have pointed out in this chapter how we may improve our methods of getting vivid impressions,
 of repeating and of tying our facts together.
 But memory is so essentially a matter of association that 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

there can be,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as Professor James points out,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

no improvement of the general or elementary faculty of memory;
 there can only be improvement of our memory for special systems of associated things.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By memorizing,
 for instance,
 a quotation a day from Shakespeare,
 we may improve our memory for literary quotations to a surprising degree.
 Each additional quotation will find many friends in the mind to tie to.
 But the memorizing of everything from Hamlet to Romeo will not necessarily aid one in retaining facts about the cotton market or the Bessemer process for desiliconizing pig iron.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us repeat:
 if we apply and use the principles discussed in this chapter,
 we will improve our manner and efficiency for memorizing anything;
 but,
 if we do not apply these principles,
 then the memorizing of ten million facts about baseball will not help us in the slightest in memorizing facts about the stock market.
 Such unrelated data cannot be tied together.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Our mind is essentially an associating machine.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SUMMARY
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The average man,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says the noted psychologist,
 Professor Carl Seashore,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

does not use above ten per cent of his actual inherited capacity for memory.
 He wastes the ninety per cent by violating the natural laws of remembering.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2.
 These 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

natural laws of remembering
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 are three:
 impression,
 repetition,
 association.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3.
 Get a deep,
 vivid impression of the thing you wish to remember.
 To do that you must-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 a.
 Concentrate.
 That was the secret of Roosevelt's memory.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 b.
 Observe closely.
 Get an accurate impression.
 A camera won't take pictures in a fog;
 neither will your mind retain foggy impressions.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 c.
 Get your impressions through as many of the senses as possible.
 Lincoln read aloud whatever he wished to remember so that he would get both a visual and an auditory impression.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 d.
 Above all else,
 be sure to get eye impressions.
 They stick.
 The nerves leading from the eye to the brain are twenty times as large as those
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 leading from the ear to the brain.
 Mark Twain could not remember the outline of his speech when he used notes;
 but when he threw away his notes and used pictures to recall his various headings,
 all his troubles vanished.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4.
 The second law of memory is repetition.
 Thousands of Mohammedan students memorize the Koran-a book about as long as the New Testa-ment-and they do it very largely through the power of repetition.
 We can memorize anything within reason if we repeat it often enough.
 But bear these facts in mind as you repeat:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 a.
 Do not sit down and repeat a thing over and over until you have it engraved on your memory.
 Go over it once or twice,
 then drop it;
 come back later and go over it again.
 Repeating at intervals,
 in that manner,
 will enable you to memorize a thing in about one-half the time required to do it at one sitting.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 b.
 After we memorize a thing,
 we forget as much during the first eight hours as we do during the next thirty days;
 so go over your notes just a few minutes before you rise to make your talk.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 5.
 The third law of memory is association.
 The only way anything can possibly be remembered at all is by associating it with some other fact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

What ever appears in the mind,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says Professor James,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

must be introduced;
 and,
 when introduced,
 it is as the associate of something already there.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 The one who thinks over his experiences most,
 and weaves them into the most systematic relation with each other,
 will be the one with the best memory.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 6.
 When you wish to associate one fact with others already in the mind,
 think over the new fact from all angles.
 Ask about it such questions as these:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Why is this so?
 How is this so?
 When is it so?
 Where is it so?
 Who said it is so?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 7.
 To remember a stranger's name,
 ask questions about it-how is it spelled,
 etc.?
 Observe his looks sharply.
 Try to connect the name with his face.
 Find out his business and try to invent some nonsense phrase that will connect his name with his business,
 such as was done in the Penn Athletic Club group.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 8.
 To remember dates,
 associate them with prominent dates already in the mind.
 For example,
 the three hundredth anniversary of Shakespeare's birth occurred during the Civil War.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 9.
 To remember the points of your address,
 arrange them in such logical order that one leads naturally to the next.
 In addition,
 one can make a nonsense sentence out of the main points-for example,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The cow smoked a cigar and hooked Napoleon,
 and the house burned down with religion.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 10.
 If,
 in spite of all precautions,
 you suddenly forget what you intended to say,
 you may be able to save yourself from complete defeat by using the last words of your last sentence as the first words in a new one.
 This can be continued until you are able to think of your next point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SPEECH BUILDING
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
WORDS OFTEN MISPRONOUNCED
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How many of the following words do you hear mispronounced almost daily?
 One may say ADdress for ad-DRESS,
 and A-dult for a-DULT,
 and find his errors undetected by many educated people;
 but who can forgive such slovenly,
 such gross faults as 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

praps
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

presidunt
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

progrum
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

?
 They are as offensive to the cultivated ear as soiled linen to the eye.
 For them and their ilk,
 there can be no excuse,
 no forgiveness,
 no explanation except sheer intellectual lethargy and frowziness.
 Their use condemns one as lacking in culture,
 as deficient in mental self-respect.
 Yet I have heard an occasional radio announcer speak of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

progrum.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Have you?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do not say:
\end_layout

