\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The study of synonyms has always been regarded as one of the most valuable of intellectual disciplines,
 independently of its great importance as a guide to the right,
 practical use of words.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

G.
 P.
 Marsh,
 Lectures On The English Language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But-And.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Poor but honest,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 suggests that the ordinary man is dishonest.
 What would 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

old but respectable
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 imply?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Calm-Cool.
 If you keep yourself from becoming excited at a train wreck,
 you are calm;
 if you don't have to try to control yourself,
 you are cool.
 If you are always composed and have poise,
 your mind is tranquil and your disposition placid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Capacity-Ability.
 (Wrong.) 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

He has an extraordinary capacity for hard work.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Capacity is the power to receive;
 ability the power to do.
 Ability includes capacity.
 An actor may have an unusual capacity for memorizing lines,
 and not have the ability to act well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can-May.
 Can denotes power and ability.
 Do not confuse can with may which refers to permission.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Can I use your knife?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 literally means have I the power to use it.
 The chances are that I have,
 unless I am paralyzed.
 If I wish to ask for permission,
 I should say,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

May I use your knife.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-RELAXING THE THROAT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Strain and tension,
 we learned in the last chapter,
 impair the voice and render it disagreeable.
 Where does this tension usually get in its deadly work?
 In what part of the body?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There can be no question about that.
 It raises its head like a viper and licks out its fiery tongue almost always in the same place:
 the throat.
 The nervous gripping of the muscles there causes roughness of the voice,
 fatigue,
 hoarseness and even sore throat.
 There is the so-called 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

teacher's sore throat,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the well-known 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

minister's sore throat,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

speaker's sore throat.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A man can converse in business all day,
 month after month,
 without suffering from a sore throat.
 Why,
 then,
 should he contract that affliction when he attempts to do considerable public speaking?
 The answer can be given in one word:
 tension.
 He does not use his organs of speech properly.
 He is nervous;
 and he unconsciously contracts the muscles of his throat.
 He takes a deep breath,
 raises his chest by muscular effort and continues to hold it high by muscular effort;
 and the strain of these chest muscles tightens his throat.
 He wants to be emphatic,
 and he strains and tightens his throat.
 He wants to be heard;
 and he tries to force the words out of his throat.
 The result?
 Breathy tones,
 harsh tones,
 unpleasant tones,
 tones that will not carry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is not the way to do it at all.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Behold,
 I show unto you a more excellent way.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Relax the throat entirely.
 It ought to be merely the chimney up which the column of air passes from your lungs.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

There must be as little consciousness of effort in the throat as possible,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says Galli-Curci.
 The old Italian singing masters used to boast:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

l'Italiano non ha gola
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The Italian singer has no throat.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 None of the great singers,
 Caruso,
 Melba,
 Patti,
 Mary Garden,
 none of them sang as if he or she had a throat.
 That is the way a speaker should speak.
 All the muscles above the collar bone should be relaxed.
 In reality,
 all the muscles from the waist up should be relaxed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How are you going to be sure of this highlydesired relaxed and open throat?
 Here is a very simple way to do it,
 one that you cannot easily forget.
 Suppose that someone has asked you,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Do the Italian singers have a throat?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 You are going to reply with a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

no.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Close your eyes.
 Think of a yawn.
 Feel yourself starting to make one.
 It begins,
 you know,
 with a deep breath-in fact,
 it is the need for more breath that causes the yawn.
 As you take the breath,
 and the moment before the yawn breaks,
 your throat is open and relaxed.
 Now,
 instead of yawning,
 speak.
 Think 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

no,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 say 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

no.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Didn't that tone sound well to your ears?
 Why?
 Because the conditions for it were right.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have learned some fundamental lessons now in tone production:
 deep diaphragmatic breathing,
 a relaxed body,
 an open throat.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Practise this exercise twenty times a day.
 Start to yawn.
 Feel the lower part of your lungs filling with air,
 pushing against the lower ribs,
 the back,
 flattening and pressing down that arched muscle called the diaphragm.
 Now,
 instead of yawning,
 speak.
 Speak a musical sentence like this:
 Lovely
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lolita drifting along in the moonlight over the murmuring lagoon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As you speak,
 feel that you are drinking in the words-not back into your throat-but up into the open chambers of your head.
 Feel the same openness in the headchambers that you feel when drinking in a deep breath through the nose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lastly,
 after taking in the deep breath,
 relax the chest entirely.
 Feel it pivoted on,
 riding on,
 the cushion of air inside.
 Your relaxed breast ought to ride on the breath just as your tires and your car ride on the air in the blown up inner tubes.
 If you do not relax your chest in this manner,
 the muscular effort that you use in holding it high will tighten your throat.
 On the other hand,
 do not construe this to mean that you are to have a caved-in chest as you are breathing.
 No.
 Hold the chest,
 not the shoulders,
 high during inspiration and then let the weight of it ride on the air pressure in the middle of your body.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
