LatexCommand href
target "privations.Pl"
literal "false"

\end_inset

'ff's husband.-Soldier leaving for army.-Skin Def't.
 -Close.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I hope that I have made plain that the first requisite in generating your warmth and enthusiasm is to prepare until you have a real message you want to get across.
 The next step is-
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
ACT IN EARNEST
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we noted in Chapter I,
 Professor James has pointed out 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

action and feeling go together;
 and,
 by regulating the action which is under the most direct control of the will,
 we can indirectly regulate the feeling which is not.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So,
 to feel earnest and enthusiastic,
 stand up and act in earnest and be enthusiastic.
 Stop leaning against the table.
 Stand tall.
 Stand still.
 Don't rock back and forth.
 Don't bob up and down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Don't shift your weight from one foot to the other and back again like a tired horse.
 In short,
 don't make a lot of nervous movements which will proclaim your lack of ease and self-possession to the housetops.
 Control yourself physically.
 It will convey a sense of poise and power.
 Stand up and stand out 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

like a strong man rejoicing to run a race.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 I repeat:
 fill your lungs with oxygen.
 Fill them to the full.
 Look straight at your audience.
 Look at them as if you had something urgent to say and as if you knew it was urgent.
 Look at them with the confidence and courage of a teacher viewing his pupils,
 for you are a teacher,
 and they are there to hear you and to be taught.
 So speak out confidently and with energy.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Lift up your voice,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 said the Prophet Isaiah,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

lift it up.
 Be not afraid.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And use emphatic gestures.
 Never mind,
 just now,
 whether they are beautiful or graceful.
 Think only of making them forceful and spontaneous.
 Make them now,
 not for the sense they will convey to others,
 but for what they will do for you.
 And they will do wonders.
 Even if you are speaking to a radio audience,
 gesture,
 gesture.
 Your gestures won't,
 of course,
 be visible to the unseen hearers,
 but the result of your gestures will be audible to them.
 They will give increased aliveness and energy to your tones and to your whole manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How often have I stopped a lifeless speaker in the midst of his talk and drilled him and compelled him to use emphatic gestures which he did not at the time feel like using.
 But the physical action of the forced gestures finally awakened and stimulated him until he gestured spontaneously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even his face brightened and his whole bearing and attitude became more earnest,
 more emphatic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acting in earnest makes one feel in earnest.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Assume a virtue,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Shakespeare advised,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

if you have it not.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Above all else,
 open your mouth,
 and speak out.
 Attorney General Wickersham once remarked to me:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The average man who attempts to speak in public cannot be heard even thirty feet away.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Does that sound exaggerated?
 I recently listened to a public address by the head of a great university.
 I sat in the fourth row and could hardly hear more than half he said.
 The ambassador of an important European nation recently delivered the commencement address before Union College;
 his delivery was so flabby that his words were almost inaudible twenty feet from the platform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If experienced speakers commit such errors,
 what is to be expected of the beginner?
 He is not used to having his voice enlarged so that it will carry over an audience;
 so,
 when he speaks with sufficient vitality,
 he will imagine that he is fairly shouting,
 and that people are ready to laugh at him.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use conversational tones;
 but enlarge them.
 Intensify them.
 We can read fine print a foot from the eye;
 but it takes bold headlines to be seen across a hall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
THE FIRST THING TO DO WHEN THE AUDIENCE GOES TO SLEEP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A country preacher once asked Henry Ward Beecher how to keep an audience awake on a hot
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sunday afternoon,
 and Beecher told him to have an usher take a sharp stick and prod the preacher.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I like that.
 It is superb.
 It is glorified common sense.
 It would do more for the average speaker than nine-tenths of all the erudite tomes that have ever been written on the art of eloquence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the surest ways to get a student to limber up and abandon and really let himself go,
 would be to knock him down before he started.
 It would put fire and spirit and aliveness into his speech.
 Actors know the value of shaking themselves awake before they make their stage entrance.
 Houdini did it by leaping about the back stage,
 striking the air vigorously with his fists,
 sparring with an imaginary antagonist.
 Mansfield sometimes deliberately planned to work himself into a perfect rage over any pretext-perhaps it was because some stage hand was breathing too audibly-any excuse that would serve to give him the heightened energy,
 the surging of spirit that he courted.
 I have seen actors standing in the wings,
 waiting for their cues and beating their breasts savagely.
 I have sent stu dents,
 just before they spoke,
 into an adjoining room to pummel their bodies until their blood leaped and their faces and eyes glowed with life.
 I frequently force a student to preface his practise talks in this course,
 repeating the A.B.C.'s with violent gestures and all the vigor and anger that he can possibly command.
 Isn't it highly desirable to go before your hearers like a thoroughbred straining at the bit?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Immediately before you speak,
 get,
 if possible,
 a thorough rest.
 The ideal thing is to undress and go
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 to bed for a few hours.
 If possible,
 follow that with a cold plunge and a vigorous rubdown.
 Better still,
 far better,
 take a swim.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Charles Frohman used to say that he hired actors because of their vitality.
 The kind of acting or speaking that counts consumes a lot of nerve force and physical energy;
 and Frohman knew it.
 I have chopped down hickory trees and split logs;
 and I have talked to audiences for two hours at a time.
 I have found one of these tasks about as exhausting as the other.
 During the War,
 Dudley Field Malone made a passionate appeal to a large audience assembled in the Century Theatre,
 New York.
 At the climax of it,
 after speaking for an hour and a half,
 he fainted from sheer exhaustion and was carried unconscious from the stage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sydney Smith described Daniel Webster as 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

a steam engine in trousers.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The most successful speakers,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 declared Beecher,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

are men of great vitality and recuperative force,
 men who have preëminently the explosive power by which they can thrust their materials out.
 They are catapults and men go down before them.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

WEASEL WORDS
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 AND ONIONS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Put energy behind what you say,
 and say it positively.
 But don't be too positive.
 Only an ignoramus is positive about everything;
 but only a weakling prefaces every remark with an it seems to me,
 or perhaps,
 or in my opinion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The almost universal trouble with beginning speakers is not that they are too positive,
 but that
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 they vitiate their talks with these timid phrases.
 I remember listening to a New York business man describe a motor trip through Connecticut.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

On the left side of the road,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 he said,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

there seemed to be a field of onions.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Now,
 there is no seeming about onions.
 They either are or are not.
 And it does not require extraordinary powers to recognize an onion field when one sees it.
 Yet this shows to what absurd lengths a speaker will sometimes go.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Weasel words
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is what Roosevelt called such expressions,
 for a weasel sucks the heart out of an egg,
 and leaves nothing but the empty shell.
 That is what these phrases do to your talk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Shrinking,
 apologetic tones and egg-shell phrases will not beget much confidence and conviction.
 Imagine business houses using such slogans as these:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

It seems to us the Underwood is the machine you will eventually buy.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

In our opinion,
 the Prudential has the strength of Gibraltar.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

We think you will use our flour eventually-why not now?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1896,
 when Bryan first ran for the presidency,
 I,
 as a boy,
 wondered why he so emphatically and so often declared that he would be elected,
 that McKinley would go down in defeat.
 The explanation is simple.
 Bryan knew that people in the mass cannot differentiate between emphasis and proof.
 He knew that if he said a thing often enough and vigorously enough,
 most of his hearers would end by believing it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The world's great leaders have always thundered forth as if there were no possibility on top of the Seven Seas of anyone invalidating their assertions.
 When Buddha was dying he did not rea-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 son or whine or argue;
 he spoke as one having authority:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Walk as I have commanded you.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Koran,
 which has been the dominant factor in millions of lives,
 immediately following the preliminary prayer,
 opens with these words:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

There is no doubt in this book;
 it is a direction.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the jailer at Philippi asked Paul,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

What must I do to be saved?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the answer was not an argument,
 an equivocation,
 an it-seems-to-me or an I-should-think assertion.
 It came,
 a superior command:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Believe on the Lord Jesus Christ,
 and thou shalt be saved.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But do not,
 as I have said,
 be too positive on all occasions.
 There are times,
 there are places,
 there are subjects,
 there are audiences,
 where too much positiveness will hinder rather than help.
 In general,
 the higher the level of intelligence of one's hearers,
 the less successful mere forceful assertions will be.
 Thinking people want to be led,
 not driven.
 They want to have the facts presented and to draw their own conclusions.
 They like to be asked questions,
 not to have a ceaseless stream of direct statements poured at them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
LOVE YOUR AUDIENCE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few years ago I had to employ and train a number of public lecturers in England.
 After painful and costly trials,
 three of them had to be dismissed,
 and one had to be sent back three thousand miles to America.
 Their main trouble was that they were not genuinely interested in serving their audiences.
 They were chiefly concerned,
 not about
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 others,
 but about themselves and their pay envelopes.
 Everyone could feel it.
 They were cold to their audiences;
 and their audiences,
 in return,
 were cold to them.
 Consequently,
 these speakers remained sounding brasses and tinkling cymbals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The well known human race is very quick to detect whether a talk is coming from above the eyebrows or back of the breast bone.
 Even a dog can sense that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I have made a special study of Lincoln as a public speaker.
 He is undoubtedly the most loved man America has ever produced;
 and unquestionably he has delivered some of America's best speeches.
 Although he was a genius in some ways,
 I am inclined to believe that his power with audiences was due,
 in no small measure,
 to his sympathy and honesty and goodness.
 He loved people.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

His heart,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 said his wife,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

is as large as his arms are long.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 He was Christlike.
 And two thousand years ago,
 one of the first books ever written on this art described the eloquent talker as 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

a good man skilled in speaking.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The secret of my success,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 said Madam Schu-mann-Heink,
 the famous prima donna,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

is absolute devotion to the audience.
 I love my audiences.
 They are all my friends.
 I feel a bond with them the moment I step before them.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 So that was the secret of her world-wide triumph.
 .
 .
 .
 Let us try to cultivate the same spirit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The finest thing in speaking is neither physical nor mental.
 It is spiritual.
 The Book that Daniel Webster had on his pillow while dying is a book that every speaker should have on his desk while living.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jesus loved men and their hearts burned within them as He talked with them by the way.
 If you want a splendid text on public speaking,
 why not read your New Testament?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SUMMARY
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I.
 Every time you speak,
 you determine the attitude of your hearers toward what you say.
 If you are lackadaisical,
 they will be lackadaisical.
 If you are only mildly concerned,
 they will be only mildly concerned.
 If you are enthusiastic,
 they will be sure to catch something of your spirit.
 Enthusiasm is one of the biggest-if not the biggest-factors in delivery.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The man who tries to be very serious or very witty,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says Martin W.
 Littleton,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

may easily fail,
 but the speaker who appeals to you with real conviction never fails.
 .
 .
 .
 If he is really deeply convinced so that he has a message for you,
 his speech will go like a flame.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3.
 In spite of the tremendous importance of this quality of contagious conviction and enthusiasm,
 most men lack it.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The essence of a good speech,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says Professor Brander Matthews,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

is that the speaker really has something which he really wants to say.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 5.
 Think over your facts,
 burn their real importance into your mind.
 Try your own enthusiasm before you attempt to convince others.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 6.
 Establish a telegraphic communication between your head and heart.
 We want you not only
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 to give us the facts but to reveal your attitude towards those facts.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 7.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Use what language you will,
 you can never say anything but what you are.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The big thing in a speech is not his words but the spirit of the man behind the words.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 8.
 To develop earnestness,
 to feel enthusiastic,
 act enthusiastic.
 Stand tall,
 look straight at your audience.
 Use emphatic gestures.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 9.
 Above all else,
 open your mouth and speak so you can be heard.
 Many speakers cannot be heard thirty feet away.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 10.
 When a country minister asked Henry Ward Beecher what to do when an audience went to sleep on a hot Sunday afternoon,
 Beecher replied,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Have an usher get a sharp stick and prod the preacher.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is one of the best bits of advice ever given on the art of public speaking.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 11.
 Don't weaken your speech with 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

weasel
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 words,
 such as 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

it seems to me,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

in my humble opinion.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 12.
 Love your audience.
\end_layout

