\begin_layout Section*
ERRORS IN ENGLISH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The language of the individual is one of the qualities by which he is judged.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Management of Men,
 E.
 L.
 Munson.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Review.
 There are seven mistakes in the first paragraph of the following selection.
 The second paragraph contains six,
 and the third has seven.
 You will note that all the errors contained in these paragraphs have been considered in the course so far.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He continued his story.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"'
\end_layout

\end_inset

I will be drownded,' thinks I,
 'but I shall do the best I can and leave the rest to God.'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I laid down on a log but it wouldn't leave me ride it.
 I set up as the end raised and run straight upon the top of a rock.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I shrunk from being hit by some piece of timber and et my heart from fear as I seen men sunk in the whirlpools.
 I would have went under surely or would have been hung by something catching around my neck,
 if I had stayed with the log.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

But I looked around and seen the bank near at hand with a clear passage to it.
 I sprung from my perch and swum for all I knowed.
 When I reached shore,
 I sung out and rung the alarm bell.
 Then I hopped a horse and run him hard to reach you people in time.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New Study Material.
 Like sometimes means similar to,
 as 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

His hat is like mine.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Occasionally,
 like means in the same manner as.
 As an example of this latter use,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

He laughs like me.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Be very sure that you never use like to introduce a subject with a verb.
 You will find below two examples where it is used improperly.
 Observe them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Right
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It looks as if it might rain.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Talk as I do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 It looks like it might rain.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Talk like I do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As-as is used in positive statements;
 so-as is used in negative statements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 She is as well as may be expected.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 It is not so good as it was last time.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 It is not as good as it was last time.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Either and neither should be used only when referring to two things;
 when designating one of three or more,
 use any one or none.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 He had all three of his saddle horses in the show ring,
 but none of them got a ribbon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 He had all three of his saddle horses in the show ring,
 but neither of them got a ribbon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 He had two sons in the school but neither of them got honors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 He had two sons in the school but none of them got honors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Either war or peace must be decided upon.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Either of three things must be passed upon by the commission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 You,
 even though it refers to one person only,
 is never followed by was.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 You were the only man there.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 You was the only man there.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Do not use except to join two clauses or sentences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 You will not get the order unless you cut your price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 You will not get the order except you cut your price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 The expression,
 had ought,
 is always incorrect.
 Examples are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 He ought to have taken the offer.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 He had ought to have taken the offer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Care-Caution.
 Care suggests watchful attention;
 caution is a stronger word and implies that strict observation must be exercised to avoid harm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A department store marks a package of dishes,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Handle with care.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We exercise caution in crossing a condemned bridge,
 or caution may keep us from attempting it.
 Watchfulness looks for a possible danger,
 wariness for a probable one.
 You must be watchful when driving a machine in city craffic;
 you must be wary in fording a swollen river.
 Loncern implies a serious but more mild interest chan is denoted by anxiety.
 One may be concerned about the outcome of an election,
 one feels anxious and distressed about a mother hurt in an accident.
 Solicitude is a stronger word than concern;
 but sug.
 gests less mental disturbance than anxiety.
 Solicitude often implies tender care;
 we speak of a parent's solicitude for a child.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Got-Secure-Receive.
 The correct meaning of got is to secure through your own desire and effort.
 In these sentences,
 for example,
 got is used incorrectly:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

What has that got to do with it?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Have you got time to listen?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

We have got to hurry.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In each of these sentences the word got should be dropped.
 It is not needed.
 It is incorrect.
 Say:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Have you time to listen?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is all right to say:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I have got his prices,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 if I have secured them.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I got the position I applied for,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is correct for it implies action on my part.
 But we violate the laws of good usage when we say,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

We got your letter this morning,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 unless,
 of course,
 we made a special trip or effort to get it.
 If the posts man brought it,
 we received it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-BREATH CONTROL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

If I were to teach a young girl right at this moment,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 declared Madame Julia Claussen,
 a wellknown concert singer,
 during the course of an interview,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I would simply ask her to take a deep breath,
 and note the expansion at the waist just above the diaphragm.
 Then I would ask her to say as many words as possible upon that breath,
 at the same time having the muscles adjacent to the diaphragm to support the breath;
 that is,
 to sustain it and not collapse or try to push it up.
 The trick is to get the most tone,
 not with the most breath,
 but with the least breath and especially the very least possible strain at the throat which must be kept in a floating,
 gossamer-like condition all the time.
 .
 .
 .
 For me the most difficult vowel is 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

ah.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The throat then is most open and the breath stream most difficult to control properly.
 Therefore I make it a habit to begin my practice with oo,
 oh,
 ah,
 ay,
 ee in succession.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Very good,
 Madame Julia Claussen.
 We are not young girls,
 and neither are we interested in singing;
 but we are going to accept your suggestions and use them to improve our speaking voices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First,
 let us take a deep breath,
 as she suggests.
 Start to yawn as you drink it in,
 deep,
 now,
 deep;
 feel your porous lungs expanding like a toy balloon;
 feel them pushing out the lower ribs at both sides and in the back.
 Feel them shoving down and flattening out that arched muscle called the diaphragm.
 Give your principal attention to the dia-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 phragm.
 It is a soft muscie.
 It needs strengtho ening.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 before the yawn breaks,
 with your throat open,
 begin to sing 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

ah.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Sing it for as long a time as your supply of breath will permit.
 How long will that be?
 That depends upon how good your breath control is.
 The natural tendency will be for your deep breath to rush out suddenly like air from a punctured balloon.
 Why?
 Because the lungs are elastic,
 they are expanded now,
 and they want to contract.
 The floating ribs have been pushed outward by the extending lungs;
 and they are tending now to press the air out of the lungs.
 The diaphragm,
 too,
 unless you control it,
 will quickly resume its arched position,
 pushing the breath out of the inflated porous lungs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 if you permit the air to escape with a rush,
 your tones will be breathy.
 They will not be clear.
 They will not be pleasant.
 They will not have carrying power.
 How,
 then,
 are we to control this escape of carrying power?
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

It is impossible,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 said Caruso,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

to sing artistically without a thorough mastery of breath control.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is also impossible to have the ideal speaking voice without it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How,
 then,
 are we to set about controlling the escape of the breath?
 Unless we are careful,
 our first tendency may be to control it by tightening the throat.
 Than that,
 what could be more ill advised?
 In the words of Madame Julia Claussen,
 the throat 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

must be kept in a floating,
 gossamerlike condition all the time.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The throat should have nothing to do with the escape of the breath.
 The throat isn't pressing against our expanded lungs.
 So we should direct our control to the things that are:
 the diaphragm and the ribs.
 Control them.
 Let them press easily,
 gently,
 as you sing 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

ah.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 See how long a time you can hold that tone firm,
 without wavering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us try the other notes that Madame Julia Claussen suggests:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

oo,
 oh,
 ah,
 ay,
 ee.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CHAPTER VI
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 ESSENTIAL ELEMENTS IN SUCCESSFUL SPEAKING
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I never allow myself to become discouraged under any circumstances.
 .
 .
 .
 The three great essentials to achieve anything worth while are,
 first,
 hard work;
 second,
 stick-to-itiveness,
 third,
 common sense.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Thomas A.
 Edison.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Much good work is lost for the lack of a little more.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

E.
 H.
 Harriman.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Never despair,
 but,
 if you do,
 work on in despair.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Edmund Burke.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Patience is the best remedy for every trouble.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

