\begin_layout Section*
CHAPTER VI
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
ESSENTIAL ELEMENTS IN SUCCESSFUL SPEAKING
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The day these lines are written,
 January 5th,
 is the anniversary of the death of Sir Ernest Shackleton.
 He died while steaming southward on the good ship 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Quest
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to explore the Antarctic.
 The first thing that attracted one's eyes on going aboard the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Quest
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 were these lines engraved on a brass plate:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

If you can dream and not make dreams your master;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 If you can think and not make thoughts your aim;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 If you can meet with triumph and disaster;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 And treat those two imposters just the same,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

If you can force your heart,
 and nerve,
 and sinew
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 To serve your turn long after they are gone;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 And so hold on when there is nothing in you
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Except the will which says to them,
 'Hold on,'
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

If you can fill the unforgiving minute
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 With sixty seconds' worth of distance run,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Yours is the earth and everything that's in it,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 And,
 what is more,
 you'll be a man,
 my son.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The spirit of the Quest,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Shackleton called those verses;
 and,
 truly,
 they are the proper spirit with which a man should start out to reach the South Pole or to gain confidence in public speaking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But that is not the spirit,
 I regret to add,
 in which all men begin the study of public speaking.
 Years ago,
 when I first engaged in educational work,
 I was astounded to learn how large a percentage of students who enrolled in night schools of all sorts grew weary and fainted by the wayside before their goals were attained.
 The number is both lamentable and amazing.
 It is a sad commentary on human nature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the sixth lesson of this course,
 and I know from experience that some of the men who are reading these lines are already growing disheartened because they have not,
 in six short weeks,
 conquered their fear of audiences and gained selfconfidence.
 What a pity,
 for 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

how poor are they that have not patience.
 What wound did ever heal but by degrees?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
THE NECESSITY OF PERSISTENCE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we start to learn any new thing,
 like French,
 or golf,
 or public speaking,
 we never advance steadily.
 We do not improve graduallry.
 We do it by sudden jerks,
 by abrupt starts.
 Then we remain stationary a time,
 or we may even slip back and lose some of the ground we have previously gained.
 These periods of stagnation,
 or retrogression,
 are well known by all psychologists;
 and they have been named 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

plateaus in the curve of learning.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Students of public speaking will sometimes be stalled for weeks on one of these plateaus.
 Work as hard as they may,
 they cannot get off it.
 The weak ones give up in despair.
 Those with grit
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 persist,
 and they find that suddenly,
 overnight,
 without their knowing how or why it has happened,
 they have made great progress.
 They have lifted from the plateau like an aeroplane.
 Abruptly they have gotten the knack of the thing.
 Abruptly they have acquired naturalness and force and confidence in their speaking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You may always,
 as we have noted elsewhere in these pages,
 experience some fleeting fear,
 some shock,
 some nervous anxiety the first few moments you face an audience.
 John Bright felt it to the end of his busy career;
 so did Gladstone;
 so did Bishop Wilberforce;
 so did a score of other eminent speakers.
 Even the greatest of the musicians have felt it in spite of their innumerable public appearances.
 Paderewski always fidgeted nervously with his cuffs immediately before he sat down at the piano.
 Nordica felt her heart racing.
 So did Sembrich.
 So did Emma Eames.
 But it vanished quickly,
 all of this audience fear,
 like a mist in the August sunshine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Their experience will be yours.
 If you will but persevere,
 you will soon eradicate everything but this initial fear;
 and that will be initial fear,
 and nothing more.
 After the first few sentences,
 you will have control of yourself.
 You will be speaking with positive pleasure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
KEEPING EVERLASTINGLY AT IT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One time a young man who aspired to study law,
 wrote to Lincoln for advice,
 and Lincoln replied:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

If you are resolutely determined to make a lawyer
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 of yourself,
 the thing is more than half done already.
 .
 .
 .
 Always bear in mind that your own resolution to succeed is more important than any other one thing.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lincoln knew.
 He had gone through it all.
 He had never,
 in his entire life,
 had more than a total of one year's schooling.
 And books?
 Lincoln once said he had walked and borrowed every book within fifty miles of his home.
 A log fire was usually kept going all night in the cabin.
 Sometimes he read by the light of that fire.
 There were cracks between the logs,
 and Lincoln often kept a book sticking in a crack.
 As soon as it was light enough to read in the morning,
 he rolled over on his bed of leaves,
 rubbed his eyes,
 pulled out the book and began de vouring it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He walked twenty and thirty miles to hear a speaker and,
 returning home,
 he practised his talks everywhere-in the fields,
 in the woods,
 before the crowds gathered at Jones' grocery at Gentryville.
 He joined literary and debating societies in New Salem and Springfield,
 and practised speaking on the topics of the day much as you are doing now as a member of this course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sense of inferiority always troubled him.
 In the presence of women he was shy and dumb.
 When he courted Mary Todd he used to sit in the parlor,
 bashful and silent,
 unable to find words,
 listening while she did the talking.
 Yet that was the man who,
 by practise and home study,
 made himself into the speaker who debated with the accomplished orator,
 Senator Douglas.
 That was the man who,
 at Gettysburg,
 and again in his second inaugural
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 address,
 rose to heights of eloquence that have rarely been attained in all the annals of mankind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Small wonder that,
 in view of his own terrific handicaps and pitiful struggle,
 he wrote:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

If you are resolutely determined to make a lawyer out of yourself,
 the thing is more than half done already.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is an excellent picture of Abraham Lincoln in the President's office.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Often when I had some matter to decide,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 said Theodore Roosevelt,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

something involved and difficult to dispose of,
 something where there were conflicting rights and interests,
 I would look up at Lincoln,
 try to imagine him in my place,
 try to figure out what he would do in the same circumstances.
 It may sound odd to you,
 but,
 frankly,
 it seemed to make my troubles easier of solution.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why not try Roosevelt's plan?
 Why not,
 if you are discouraged and feeling like giving up the fight to make a speaker of yourself,
 why not pull out of your pocket one of the five dollar bills that bear a likeness of Lincoln,
 and ask yourself what he would do under the circumstances.
 You know what he would do.
 You know what he did do.
 After he had been beaten by Stephen A.
 Douglas in the race for the U.
 S.
 Senate,
 he admonished his followers not to 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

give up after one nor one hundred defeats.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
THE CERTAINTY OF REWARD
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How I wish I could get you to prop this book open on your breakfast table every morning for a week until you had memorized these words from
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Professor William James,
 the famous Harvard psychologist:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let no youth have any anxiety about the upshot of his education,
 whatever the line of it may be.
 If he keeps faithfully busy each hour of the working day,
 he may safely leave the final result to itself.
 He can,
 with perfect certainty,
 count on waking up some fine morning to find himself one of the competent ones of his generation,
 in whatever pursuit he may have singled out.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And now,
 with the renowned Professor James to fall back upon,
 I shall go so far as to say that if you pursue this course faithfully and with enthusiasm,
 and keep right on practising intelligently,
 you may confidently hope to wake up one fine morning and find yourself one of the competent speakers of your city or community.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regardless of how fantastic that may sound to you now,
 it is true as a general principle.
 Exceptions,
 of course,
 there are.
 A man with an inferior mentality and personality,
 and with nothing to talk about,
 is not going to develop into a local Daniel Webster;
 but,
 within reason,
 the assertion is correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let me illustrate by a concrete example:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Former Governor Stokes of New Jersey attended the closing banquet of a public speaking class at Trenton.
 He remarked that the talks that he had heard the students make that evening were as good as the speeches that he had heard in the House of Representatives and Senate at Washington.
 Those Trenton speeches were made by business men who had been tongue-tied with audience-fear a few months previously.
 They were not incipient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ciceros,
 those New Jersey business men;
 they were typical of the business men one finds in any American city.
 Yet they woke up one fine morning to find themselves among the competent speakers of their city.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entire question of your success as a speaker hinges upon only two things-your native ability,
 and the depth and strength of your desires.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

In almost any subject,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 said Professor James,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

your passion for the subject will save you.
 If you only care enough for a result,
 you will most certainly attain it.
 If you wish to be rich,
 you will be rich;
 if you wish to be learned,
 you will be learned;
 if you wish to be good,
 you will be good.
 Only you must,
 then,
 really wish these things and wish them with exclusiveness,
 and not wish at the same time a hundred other incompatible things just as strongly.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And Professor James might have added,
 with equal truth,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

If you want to be a confident public speaker,
 you will be a confident public speaker.
 But you must really wish it.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I have known and carefully watched literally thousands of men trying to gain self-confidence and the ability to talk in public.
 Those that succeeded were,
 in only a few instances,
 men of unusual brilliancy.
 For the most part,
 they were the ordinary run of business men that you will find in your own home town.
 But they kept on.
 Smarter men sometimes got discouraged or too deeply immersed in money making,
 and they did not get very far;
 but the ordinary individual with grit and singleness of purpose-at the end of the chapter,
 he was at the top.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is only human and natural.
 Don't you see the same thing occurring all the time in commerce and the professions?
 Rockefeller said some time ago that the first essential for success in business was patience.
 It is likewise one of the first essentials for success in this course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marshal Foch led to victory by far the greatest army the world has ever seen,
 and he declared that he had only one virtue:
 never despairing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the French had retreated to the Marne in 1914,
 General Joffre instructed the generals under him in charge of two million men to stop retreating and begin an offensive.
 This new battle,
 one of the most decisive in the world's history,
 had raged for two days when General Foch,
 in command of Joffre's center,
 sent him one of the most impressive messages in military records:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

My center gives way.
 My right recedes.
 The situation is excellent.
 I shall attack.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That attack saved Paris.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 So,
 my dear speaker,
 when the fight seems hardest and most hopeless,
 when your center gives way and your right recedes,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

the situation is excellent.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Attack!
 Attack!
 Attack,
 and you will save the best part of your manhood-your courage and faith.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CLIMBING THE 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

WILD KAISER
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few summers ago,
 I started out to scale a peak in the Austrian Alps called the Wilder Kaiser.
 Baedeker said that the ascent was difficult,
 and a guide was essential for amateur climbers.
 We,
 a
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 friend and I,
 had none,
 and we were certainly amateurs;
 so a third party asked us if we thought we were going to succeed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Of course,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we replied.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

What makes you think so?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 he inquired.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Others have done it without guides,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 I said,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

so I know it is within reason,
 and I never undertake anything thinking defeat.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an Alpinist,
 I am the merest,
 bungling novice;
 but that is the proper psychology for anything from essaying public speaking to an assault on Mount Everest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Think success in this course.
 See yourself in your imagination talking in public with perfect selfcontrol.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easily in your power to do this.
 Believe that you will succeed.
 Believe it firmly and you will then do what is necessary to bring success about.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Admiral Dupont gave half a dozen excellent reasons why he had not taken his gunboats into Charleston harbor.
 Admiral Farragut listened intently to the recital.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

But there was another reason that you have not mentioned,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 he replied.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

What is that?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 questioned Admiral Dupont.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 The answer came:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

You did not believe you could do it.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most valuable thing that most members acquire from a course in public speaking is an increased confidence in themselves,
 an additional faith in their ability to achieve.
 And than that,
 what is more important for one's success in almost any undertaking?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
THE WILL TO WIN
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is a bit of sage advice from Elbert Hubbard that I cannot refrain from quoting.
 If the average man would only apply and live the wisdom contained in it,
 he would be happier,
 more prosperous:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Whenever you go out of doors,
 draw the chin in,
 carry the crown of the head high and fill the lungs to the utmost;
 drink in the sunshine;
 greet your friends with a smile and put soul into every handclasp.
 Do not fear being misunderstood and do not waste a minute thinking about your enemies.
 Try to fix firmly in your mind what you would like to do,
 and then,
 without veering of direction,
 you will move straight to the goal.
 Keep your mind on the great and splendid things you would like to do,
 and then,
 as the days go gliding by,
 you will find yourself unconsciously seizing upon the opportunities that are required for the fulfilment of your desire,
 just as the coral insect takes from the running tide the elements it needs.
 Picture in your mind the able,
 earnest,
 useful person you desire to be,
 and the thought you hold is hourly transforming you into that particular individual.
 .
 .
 .
 Thought is supreme.
 Preserve a right mental attitude-the attitude of courage,
 frankness and good cheer.
 To think rightly is to create.
 All things come through desire and every sincere prayer is answered.
 We become like that on which our hearts are fixed.
 Carry your chin in and the crown of your head high.
 We are gods in the chrysalis.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Napoleon,
 Wellington,
 Lee,
 Grant,
 Foch-all great military leaders have recognized that an army's will to win and its confidence in its ability to win,
 do more than any other one thing to determine its success.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Ninety thousand conquered men,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says Marshall Foch,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

retire before ninety thousand conquering men only because they have had enough,
 because they no longer believe in victory,
 because they are demoralized-at the end of their moral resistance.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words,
 the ninety thousand retiring men are not really whipped physically;
 but they are conquered because they are whipped mentally,
 because they have lost their courage and confidence.
 There is no hope for an army like that.
 There is no hope for a man like that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chaplain Frazier,
 the ranking chaplain of the U.S.
 Navy,
 interviewed those who wished to enlist for the chaplaincy service during the World War.
 When asked what qualities were essential for the success of a navy chaplain,
 he replied with four 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\prime}s$
\end_inset

 :
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Grace,
 gumption,
 grit,
 and guts.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Those are also the requisites for success in speaking.
 Take them as your motto.
 Take this Robert Service poem as your battle song:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

When you're lost in the wild,
 and you're scared as a child,
 And death looks you bang in the eye.
 And you're sore as a boil,
 it's according to Hoyle To cock your revolver and .
 .
 .
 die.
 But the code of a man,
 says:
 'Fight all you can,' And self-dissolution is barred.
 In hunger and woe,
 oh,
 it's easy to blow .
 .
 .
 It's the hell-served-for-breakfast that's hard.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

You're sick of the game!
 'Well,
 now,
 that's a shame.' You're young and you're brave and you're bright.
 'You've had a raw deal!' I know-but don't squeal.
 Buck up,
 do your damnedest,
 and fight.
 It's the plugging away that will win you the day,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So don't be a piker,
 old pard!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Just draw on your grit;
 it's so easy to quit:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 It's the keeping-your-chin-up that's hard.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

It's easy to cry that you're beaten-and die.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 It's easy to crawfish and crawl;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 But to fight and to fight when hope's out of sight,
 Why,
 that's the best game of them all!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 And though you come out of each gruelling bout All broken and beaten and scarred,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Just have one more try-it's dead easy to die,
 It's the keeping-on-living that's hard.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SUMMARY
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We never learn anything-be it golf,
 French,
 or public speaking-by means of gradual improve.
 ment.
 We advance by sudden jerks and abrupt starts.
 Then we may remain stationary for a few weeks,
 or even lose some of the proficiency we have gained.
 Psychologists call these periods of stagnation 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

plateaus in the curve of learning.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We may strive hard for a long time and not be able to get off one of these 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

plateaus
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and onto an upward ascent again.
 Some men,
 not realizing this curious fact about the way we progress,
 get discouraged on these plateaus and abandon all effort.
 That is extremely regrettable,
 for if they were to persist,
 if they were to keep on practising,
 they would suddenly find that they had lifted like an æroplane and made tremendous progress again overnight.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You may never be able to speak without some nervous anxiety just before you begin.
 Bright,
 Gladstone,
 Bishop Wilberforce,
 to the end of their careers,
 experienced some initial nervousness.
 But,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 if you will persevere,
 you will soon eradicate everything but this initial fear;
 and,
 after you have spoken for a few seconds,
 that too will disappear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Professor James has pointed out that one need have no anxiety about the upshot of his education,
 that if he keeps faithfully busy,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

he can,
 with perfect cerainty,
 count on waking up some fine morning to find himself one of the competent ones of his generation,
 in whatever pursuit he may have singled out.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This psychological truth that the famous sage of Harvard has enunciated,
 applies to you and your efforts in learning to speak.
 There can be no question about that.
 The men who have succeeded in this course have not been,
 as a general rule,
 men of extraordinary ability.
 But they were endowed with persistence and dogged determination.
 They kept on.
 They arrived.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Think success in your public speaking work.
 You will then do the things necessary to bring success about.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If you get discouraged,
 try Roosevelt's plan of looking at Lincoln's picture and asking yourself what he would have done under similar circumstances.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The ranking chaplain of the U.
 S.
 Navy during the world war said that the qualities essential for the success of a chaplain in the service could be enumerated with four words commencing with 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 What are they?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SPEECH BUILDING
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
WORDS OFTEN MISPRONOUNCED
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many persons have the careless habit of dropping the 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 in words ending in ing.
 To correct this tendency the following passage from Southey's 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The Cataract of Lodore
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 should be read aloud daily with distinctness and precision until the student's own ears become sensitive to his sins of omission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cataract strong
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Then plunges along,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Striking and raging
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 As if a war waging
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Its caverns and rocks among;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rising and leaping,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Sinking and creeping,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Swelling and sweeping,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Showering and springing,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Flying and flinging,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Writhing and wringing,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Eddying and whisking,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Spouting and frisking,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Turning and twisting,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Around and around
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 With endless rebound:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Smiting and fighting,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 A sight to delight in;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Confounding,
 astounding,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Dizzying and deafening the ear with its sound.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Collecting,
 projecting,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Receding and speeding,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And shocking and rocking,
 And darting and parting,
 And threading and spreading,
 And whizzing and hissing,
 And dropping and skipping,
 And hitting and splitting,
 And shining and twining,
 And rattling and battling,
 And shaking and quaking,
 And pouring and roaring,
 And waving and raving,
 And tossing and crossing,
 And flowing and going,
 And running and stunning,
 And foaming and roaming,
 And dinning and spinning,
 And dropping and hopping,
 And working and jerking,
 And guggling and struggling,
 And heaving and cleaving,
 And moaning and groaning,
 And glittering and frittering,
 And gathering and feathering,
 And whitening and brightening,
 And quivering and shivering,
 And hurrying and skurrying,
 And thundering and floundering;
 Dividing and gliding and sliding,
 And falling and brawling and sprawling,
 And driving and riving and striving,
 And sprinkling and twinkling and wrinkling,
 And sounding and bounding and rounding,
 And bubbling and troubling and doubling,
 And grumbling and rumbling and tumbling,
 And clattering and battering and shattering;
 Retreating and beating and meeting and sheeting,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Delaying and straying and playing and spraying,
 Advancing and prancing and glancing and dancing,
 Recoiling,
 turmoiling and toiling and boiling,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And gleaming and streaming and steaming and beaming,
 And rushing and flushing and brushing and gushing,
 And flapping and rapping and clapping and slapping,
 And curling and whirling and purling and twirling,
 And thumping and plumping and bumping and jumping,
 And dashing and flashing and splashing and clashing;
 And so never ending,
 but always descending,
 Sounds and motions forever and ever are blending,
 All at once and all o'er,
 with a mighty uproar,
 And this way the water comes down at Lodore.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
ERRORS IN ENGLISH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

There is no need to tell an experienced man of the world what books you have read,
 with whom you have been in the habit of associating,
 or what your degree of culture is.
 He can learn all these things from your speech.
 'Thy conversation betrayeth thee.' Every sentence you utter betrays its source.
 He can tell whether your speech is pauperized or vulgarized by association with the ignorant and the vulgar,
 or enriched and refined by companionship with the well-bred and educated.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Orison S.
 Marden.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Review.
 There are five errors in the following paragraph:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As you was the only man there,
 you had ought to have offered to help.
 Neither of the three ladies could do it like you could.
 They did not know you as intimately as we do and may think you boorish.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 New Study Material.
 Rule:
 A singular subject demands a singular verb.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 If coffee doesn't agree,
 use Postum.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

If coffee don't agree,
 use Postum.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Advertisement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 The landlord,
 as near as I can find out,
 doesn't intend to make any repairs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 John Adams,
 a short time before his death,
 in speaking of his ill health,
 said to Daniel Webster:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I am a poor tenant occupying a house much shattered by time.
 It sways and trembles with every wind,
 and has in fact almost gone to decay;
 and,
 what is worse,
 sir,
 the landlord,
 as near as I can find out,
 don't intend to make any repairs.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 A sack of potatoes was sitting by the stove.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 A sack of potatoes were sitting by the stove.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 Neither and either,
 as pronouns,
 always require a singular verb.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Neither of the offers was accepted.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Neither of the offers were accepted.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 Either of the houses is suitable.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Either of the houses are suitable.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 If a first personal pronoun is used with some other word or words in a compound subject,
 it should stand second in accordance with courtesy.
 The verb must agree with this pronoun in number if or is used as the connecting word.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 He or I am going.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 He or I are going.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 The school in a body,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 as a representative,
 am going.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 The school in a body,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 as a representative,
 are going.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the sake of euphony,
 it is better to avoid such awkward construction even though it may be correct.
 It is much easier to say 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Either the school in a body will attend,
 or I shall go as its representative.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 There is always some difficulty in the use of verbs after what are known as collective nouns.
 A collective noun is one that stands for a group or a class considered as a unit.
 The singular verb is always used when the group is considered as a unit.
 For example:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The jury is ready to bring in its verdict.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Occasionally,
 the component parts of the group are considered as acting each for himself or as having diverse opinions.
 In this case the verb must be plural.
 For example:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The jury were divided in their opinions.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 Certain words denoting quantity are usually followed by the word of.
 Such words are plenty,
 abundance,
 residence,
 rest,
 variety,
 etc.
 In this class would be included fractions.
 In all such cases,
 if of is followed by a noun denoting a plural number,
 a plural verb must be used.
 If there is a singular subject,
 of course a singular verb is the one that is correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Nine-tenths of the land is under water.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 One-quarter of the men were without intelligence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Plenty of people are without means of support.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 A variety of silks were on the counter.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Occasionally we speak about something that is plural in form but which still represents a singular thing.
 In this case it takes the singular verb.
 Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Six dollars is too dear.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 Two years is a long sentence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clear-Translucent.
 Water may be clear;
 but ground glass,
 which allows light,
 but not form or color,
 to pass through it,
 is translucent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compare-Contrast.
 To compare things is to seek qualities they possess in common;
 to contrast is to search for differences.
 You might compare a Ford to a cheap car,
 but you would contrast it with a Pierce-Arrow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compulsion-Obligation.
 Compulsion means forced by physical powers;
 obligation refers to a moral necessity.
 During the war some who felt no obligation to join the army were compelled to put on khaki.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concise-Brief.
 A concise address is condensed;
 a brief address is merely short.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Trite suggests a loss of novelty and interest by constant use.
 The hackneyed thing is worn and commonplace.
 The word comes from the hackney carriage or hacks that were used and knocked about by everyone.
 Banal,
 meaning commonplace,
 was originally a feudal word.
 A ban or proclamation was issued decreeing that every tenant should bake his bread in the common oven and use the common mill.
 This came to be called the banal mill,
 so the word banal means much used and common to all.
 Stale suggests something that is tasteless with age.
 Insipid means without taste or flavor.
 Fapid suggests the loss of life and flavor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-USING THE TIP OF THE TONGUE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Caruso attributed much of his success as a singer to his extraordinary command of his tongue.
 So does Madame Galli-Curci.
 So do a host of other singers.
 Caruso trained until the tip of his tongue was extremely strong and agile.
 He made the tip do all the work while the back of the tongue lay inert and relaxed.
 That is extremely important,
 for the muscles at the back of the tongue are connected with the larynx.
 So using that part of the tongue causes unnecessary tension and constriction in the throat.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the very best ways to develop strength and activity in the end of the tongue is by trilling the sound of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Sound it incessantly like a tattoo.
 Imitate a machine gun in the distance.
 It is not merely a succession of R sounds that is wanted;
 it is a trill.
 Did you ever see the rattles on a rattlesnake vibrating rapidly in anger just before he strikes?
 If so,
 you will have some idea of the way the tip of your tongue ought to trill against the roof of your mouth just back of your front teeth.
 Haven't you heard a woodpecker on a rotten limb in early spring?
 The trill you make ought to be as rapid as his staccato.
 This trilling is something like the roll of a kettle drum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Start to say burr;
 when you come to the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 sound,
 break into a trill.
 Brrrrrrrrrrr.
 Try the same exercise with cur and slur.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now start to yawn,
 breathing deeply,
 feeling the activity in the middle of the body.
 .
 .
 .
 Before you
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 break into the yawn,
 start to trill the sound of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Trill it as long as your breath will permit.
 Use the methods of breath control described in Chapter V.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Trilling the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an important exercise;
 but do not imagine that doing it and the other voice exercises in class once a week for sixty seconds and ignoring them the rest of the time,
 will produce the desired results.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The gods,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 said Emerson,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

sell everything at a fair price.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The fair price that you must pay for voice improvement is practise,
 practise,
 practise.
 These exercises,
 however,
 do not need to consume any of the time usually devoted to other things;
 you can do them mornings in your bathtub.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Read the following poem aloud often.
 Feel the tip of the tongue touching quickly,
 decisively,
 against the back of the teeth.
 Feel the tip of it striking off the emphatic ideas with a neat,
 elastic touch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SONG OF THE BROOK
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I come from haunts of coot and hern,
 I make a sudden sally,
 And sparkle out among the fern,
 To bicker down a valley.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By thirty hills I hurry down,
 Or slip between the ridges,
 By twenty thorps,
 a little town,
 And half a hundred bridges.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Till at last by Philip's farm I flow To join the brimming river,
 For men may come and men may go,
 But I go on forever.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I chatter over stony ways,
 In little sharps and trebles,
 I bubble into eddying bays,
 I babble on the pebbles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With many a curve my banks I fret By many a field and fallow,
 And many a fairy foreland set With willow-weed and mallow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I chatter,
 chatter,
 as I flow To join the brimming river,
 For men may come and men may go,
 But I go on forever.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I wind about,
 and in and out,
 With here a blossom sailing,
 And here and there a lusty trout,
 And here and there a grayling,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And here and there a foamy flake Upon me,
 as I travel With many a silvery water-break Above the golden gravel,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And draw them all along,
 and flow To join the brimming river,
 For men may come and men may go,
 But I go on forever.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I steal by lawns and grassy plots,
 I slide by hazel covers;
 I move the sweet forget-me-nots That grow for happy lovers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I slip,
 I slide,
 I gloom,
 I glance,
 Among my skimming swallows;
 I make the netted sunbeam dance Against my sandy shallows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I murmur under moon and stars In brambly wildernesses;
 I linger by my shingly bars,
 I loiter round my cresses;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And out again I curve and flow To join the brimming river,
 For men may come and men may go,
 But I go on forever.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 -Tennyson.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 After you have read this poem through once in the manner we have just indicated,
 read it a second time,
 employing the principles that Madame Julia Claussen discussed in the voice exercises given in Chapter V.
 Breathe from the diaphragm.
 Prepare to yawn.
 Speak.
 Think of drinking in the sound up into the head chambers-not into the throat.
 Control your diaphragm.
 Keep the air from rushing out.
 See if you can read the entire poem distinctly with four breaths.
\end_layout

