\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

There are two people I must please-God and Garfield.
 I must live with Garfield here,
 with God hereafter.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - James A.
 Garfield.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A speaker may follow the directions I have set down in this lesson and still have a hundred faults.
 He may talk in public just as he does in conversation and consequently,
 he may speak with an unpleasant voice and make grammatical errors and be awkward and offensive and do a score of unpleasant things.
 A man's natural method of every day talking may need a vast number of improvements.
 Perfect your natural method of talking in conversation,
 and then carry that method to the platform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SUMMARY
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I.
 There is something besides the mere words in a talk which counts.
 It is the flavor with which they are delivered.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

It is not so much what you say as how you say it.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2.
 Many speakers ignore their hearers,
 stare over their heads or at the floor.
 They seem to be delivering a soliloquy.
 There is no sense of communication,
 no give and take between the audience and the speaker.
 That kind of attitude would kill a conversation;
 it also kills a speech.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3 Good delivery is conversational tone and directness enlarged.
 Talk to the Chamber of Commerce just as you would to John Smith.
 What is the Chamber of Commerce,
 after all,
 but a collection of John Smiths?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4.
 Every man has the ability to deliver a talk.
 If you question this statement,
 try it out for yourself;
 knock down the most ignorant man you know;
 when he gets on his feet,
 he will probably say some things,
 and his manner of saying them will be almost
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 flawless.
 We want you to take that same naturalness with you when you speak in public.
 To develop it,
 you must practise.
 Don't imitate others.
 If you speak spontaneously you will speak differently from anyone else in the world.
 Put your own individuality,
 your own characteristic manner into your delivery.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 5.
 Talk to your hearers just as if you expected them to stand up in a moment and talk back to you.
 If they were to rise and ask you questions,
 your delivery would almost be sure to improve emphatically and at once.
 So imagine that someone has asked you a question,
 and that you are repeating it.
 Say aloud,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

You ask how do I know this?
 I'll tell you.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 .
 .
 .
 That sort of thing will seem perfectly natural;
 it will break up the formality of your phraseology;
 it will warm and humanize your manner of talking.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 6.
 Put your heart into your talking.
 Real emotional sincerity will help more than all the rules in Christendom.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 7.
 Here are four things that all of us do unconsciously in earnest conversation.
 But do you do them when you are talking in public?
 Most people do not.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 a.
 Do you stress the important words in a sentence and subordinate the unimportant ones?
 Do you give almost every word including the,
 and,
 but,
 approximately the same amount of at tention,
 or do you speak a sentence in much the same way that you say MassaCHUsetts?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 b.
 Does the pitch of your voice flow up and down the scale from high to low and back again
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 -as the pitch of a little child does when speaking?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 c.
 Do you vary your rate of speaking,
 running rapidly over the unimportant words,
 spending more time on the ones you wish to make stand out?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 d.
 Do you pause before and after your important ideas?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SPEECH BUILDING
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
WORDS OFTEN MISPRONOUNCED
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

In order to deserve a place among the best speakers,
 it is not enough that one should have what is commonly termed a good education and good sense:
 he must have paid particular attention to the subject of pronunciation-unless he has been surrounded during the whole period of his education with none but correct speakers,
 which is seldom or never the case,
 at least in this country.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Joseph Thomas,
 M.D.,
 LL.D.
\end_layout

