\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New Study Material.
 This is to be a lesson on the number of pronouns used with certain ordinary words.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 Each,
 one,
 anyone,
 anybody,
 everyone,
 and everybody are singular,
 and singular pronouns must be used in referring to them.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 He never let anyone feel that he had made a mistake.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 He never let anyone feel that one had made a mistake.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 He never let anyone feel that they had made a mistake.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Everybody said he had a good time.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 (If women are referred to exclusively) Everybody said she had a good time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 Everybody said they had a good time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Anybody else would at least have said good-bye when he went away.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 Anybody else would at least have said good-bye when they went away.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Everyone ought to mind his own business.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
PUBLIC SPEAKING
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 Everyone ought to mind their own business.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Each of us is free to follow his own impulses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 Each of us is free to follow our own impulses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Sometimes one just feels as if one had to rest awhile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 Somecimes one just feels as if they had to rest awhile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 If you are talking about several subjects connected by and,
 and these subjects are preceded by each,
 every,
 or no,
 you must use the singular pronoun.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Each movement and each gesture has its meaning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 Each movement and each gesture has their meaning.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 If the antecedent is female,
 feminine pronouns are used.
 Otherwise,
 masculine pronouns are used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 If you have the pronoun one as a subject,
 you may use one's or his in connection with it,
 as,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

One should do one's (or his) best before an audience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Egoism is an excessive love of oneself,
 selfishness.
 It is the very opposite of altruism.
 Self-conceit is a flattering opinion of one's own abilities.
 Egotism shows self-conceit by words and acts.
 It reveals
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 egoism.
 One may be self-conceited and have the good taste to hide it;
 the egotistical man parades his importance.
 Pride is high-and sometimes ex-cessive-self-respect.
 It may be justified,
 or it may be unreasonable,
 conceit.
 A proud man may or may not reveal his pride.
 Vanity is a show of pride.
 The vain person longs to be noticed,
 and admired,
 and appraised.
 Vanity literally means empty.
 It is often applied to pride in such shallow things as dress and personal appearance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imprudent literally means not seen before-hence not taking results into account.
 Rash originally meant quick,
 and has now come to mean overhasty.
 A rash man does things on a momentary impulse,
 without deliberation.
 Foolhardy literally means a brave fool.
 The adventurous man gets a pleasure out of incurring risks.
 The adventurous man would rather conduct concert tours than to have an established hardware business.
 Precipitate,
 like the word precipice,
 is derived from two Latin words and literally means head before or headlong.
 A precipitate action is like plunging headlong over a cliff.
 Other words with somewhat similar meanings are:
 Hasty,
 foolish,
 ill-advised,
 unwise,
 indiscreet,
 heedless,
 thoughtless,
 incautious,
 injudicious,
 impulsive,
 hazardous,
 venturesome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-BRIGHT AND ATTRACTIVE TONES
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are three exercises which,
 if faithfully followed,
 will help to brighten your voice,
 to make it more attractive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Develop nasal resonance.
 Take a deep breath,
 and note the free,
 open,
 expansive sensation in your nose as the air is rushing in.
 Repeat the following syllables.
 Pitch them in the nose.
 Dwell on the 
\begin_inset Formula $ng$
\end_inset

 sounds at the end of each word,
 for two or three seconds.
 Let them ring in the nasal cavities like the sound of a bell.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Singing Wringing
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Bringing
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Clinging
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Flinging
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Winging
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Hanging Banging
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Longing Wronging 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For some strange reason,
 practising the falsetto voice develops a bright quality in our ordinary speaking tones.
 Do you know what we mean by the falsetto?
 I think you can get it by following these directions:
 pitch your voice in the highest tones of which you are capable-almost a shriek.
 It is a funny tone,
 very effeminate.
 It will soon tire you.
 Don't practise it after you begin to feel a strain.
 Try this verse in a falsetto voice:
 
\end_layout

