\begin_layout Standard
Can you pronounce correctly all the italicized words in the following story?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once upon a time,
 a stolid and senile Prince in the Orient read a poem about love.
 With the advent of spring,
 a hunger for romance stole over him,
 and he was unable to combat it.
 It was so exquisite,
 so formidable,
 so inexplicable,
 so delicious,
 so dolorous,
 so shaking and quaking,
 that he did not even desire to combat it.
 He felt that no one in the wide domains of his native land could understand the marvelous melody that swept through his heart.
 Conse-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 quently,
 he began to frequent the harbor,
 watching the stately ships sail in with high masts through the mists.
 His finances hardly permitted travel;
 so he went about incognito,
 using an alias,
 while he sold alternately brooms and cigar store coupons until he was able to stand the financial strain of a trip to Seattle.
 There he met a fragile widow,
 who had also recently divorced a drug addict.
 Although he was not conversant with her language,
 he was an expert flatterer.
 However,
 she was tepid to his advances.
 She counted the cost because she did not want to marry in haste when her own mind was hazy.
 She hissed in his face that she was not interested in his proposal,
 that marriage with him would be horrid,
 despicable,
 contrary to her ideals.
 He received his chastisement in silence,
 tore up the trousseau that he had depleted his finances to purchase,
 and,
 moaning and groaning,
 he sailed back to Honolulu.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
ERRORS IN ENGLISH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this,
 the first chapter in the second half of the course,
 there will be no specific review.
 Chapter VIII and the reviews in the preceding chapters examined the use of every word to which attention had been called.
 We shall now start on the study of various other ordinary mistakes which are made in the English language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 Every pronoun which is the subject of a verb must be in the nominative case,
 regardless of whether the verb is expressed or understood.
 In other words,
 when a pronoun is the subject of a verb,
 its form used should be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
<lyxtabular version="3" rows="3" columns="2">
<features tabularvalignment="middle">
<column alignment="left" valignment="top">
<column alignment="left" valignment="top">
<row>
<cell alignment="left" valignment="top" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 not me
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="left" valignment="top" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
we not us
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="left" valignment="top" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
he not him
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="left" valignment="top" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
they not them
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="left" valignment="top" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
she not her
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="left" valignment="top" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
who not whom
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 He can do it as well as 1 .
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 He can do it as well as me.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 (The last word in this sentence is the subject of the understood verb can;
 so this is equivalent to saying,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

He can do it as well as me can do it.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 
\begin_inset Formula $He$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 were the first ones here.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Him and me were the first ones here.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 
\begin_inset Formula $We$
\end_inset

 Americans will have to take a more active part in world affairs.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Us Americans will have to take a more active part in world affairs.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 (Leave out the word Americans and the mistake shocks the ears of even the most undiscerning.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 Lincoln was only about twelve years older than 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Lincoln was only about twelve years older than me.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An ex-senator in an interview in the New York Times,
 June 25,
 1922.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 (Than is a conjunction and takes the same case after it as before.
 The me in the sentence just quoted is really the subject of an understood verb.
 If the entire sentence were written,
 it would read,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Lincoln was only about twelve years older than me am old.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This lamentable error is very common.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Do not use a noun and its pronoun when the pronoun immediately follows the noun.
 Examples are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Thy rod and Thy staff comfort me.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Thy rod and Thy staff they comfort me.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Such cumpound pronouns,
 as myself,
 itself,
 ourselves,
 etc.,
 are never to be used as subjects or objects.
 This usage often happens because the speaker or writer is not sure whether to use a nominative or objective pronoun.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Mr.
 Jones and you will handle the work.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Mr.
 Jones and yourself will handle the work.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Kight:
 He handed the money to Jim and me.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 He handed the money to Jim and myself.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 It was they who concealed their assets.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 It was themselves who concealed their assets.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 They may be used,
 however,
 to refer to the subject or to express emphasis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 The man hurt himself.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 The girl herself told me so.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 N'ever use hisself,
 theirself,
 ourself,
 and theirselves.
 These are not in the language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fair man attempts to be honest and just and impartial.
 The open man speaks freely and exactly what is in his mind.
 The frank man does it from a natural dislike of restraint.
 The ingenuous man
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 has a natural simplicity and regard for truth that prompt him to confess his faults and to speak without any reserve.
 (Ingenuous must not be confused with ingenious,
 meaning clever at contriving,
 deverly contrived.) The sincere man never pretends to be anything that he is not;
 he is genuine,
 real.
 A man who speaks openly on occasions may not naturally be frank and fair.
 A frank man may not go so far in his outspokenness and confessions as the ingenuous person.
 The sincere man may not speak freely,
 but he never falsely assumes to be what he is not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Candid,
 candle and chandelier all come from the same Latin word candere,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

to be of glowing white.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A candid opinion is a glowing white,
 shining opinion giving light on both sides without any attempt at concealment.
 The unsophisticated person is sound and genuine,
 artless,
 innocent.
 He does not deal in sophistry.
 Unreserved implies freedom and frankness in words and action.
 The undesigning individual has no schemes or plots or selfish ends to serve.
 The unvarnished statement has no gloss;
 it does not attempt to smooth over anything with fair words.
 Other words related in meaning to these are:
 artless,
 free-spoken,
 guileless,
 konest,
 impartial,
 open,
 plain-spoken,
 equitable,
 unaffected,
 undisguised,
 unfeigned,
 straightforward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-RELAXING THE JAW
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the voice exercises for Chapters III and IV we pointed out the necessity for relaxation,
 especially of the throat.
 The jaw also should be relaxed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of us are inclined to hold it rigidly.
 And what is the result?
 The tone is forced to squeeze itself out;
 so it becomes thin and hard.
 Such a tone,
 made under such conditions,
 does not carry well.
 Our breath is molded into words in our mouth very largely by means of our lips and tongue-the tongue playing the principal part.
 The set jaw distorts this mouth-mold,
 and interferes with the beauty and precision of the sounds which should flow from it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides,
 stiff jaws are very liable to result in clumsy tongues;
 but it is tongue speed and firmness and elasticity that we prize.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Try these exercises for surrendering the jaw.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Drop the head on the breast,
 until your chin is touching your shirt.
 Raise all of the head now except the lower jaw.
 If you relax it thoroughly,
 gravity will hold it down just as gravity pulls your hands down to your sides when you relax them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Sit with your jaw relaxed in the mouth-open,
 dull-eyed attitude of an idiot until the jaw feels like a dead weight hanging from the rest of the head.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Put your fingers about half an inch in front of your ears where the lower jawbone hinges.
 Open the jaw deliberately.
 Chew as if you were masticating your food.
 Note the action underneath your finger tips.
 Now close the mouth,
 surrender the jaw this time and let it fall of its own dead weight.
 If you have done it correctly,
 if you have not used force,
 you will not feel the action under your finger tips this time that you felt before.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When you are trying to overhear a conversation in the distance,
 and you can hardly understand
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 it,
 what do you do?
 You unconsciously take a deep breath,
 let your mouth fall open and listen intently,
 don't you?
 Imagine you are now listening under such circumstances.
 Imagine that you have sud denly heard in that distant conversation,
 something that has surprised you exceedingly.
 What do you do?
 You expand and lift your body,
 take a deeper breath and your throat opens unconsciously.
 Now,
 say 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Oh,
 do you know what he said?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Doesn't the tone flow out easily and freely?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remember that the only way you can obtain command of the jaw is by relaxing it,
 so practise these exercises until your jaw is your docile servant,
 not a stiff,
 set and obstreperous one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Review Exercise:
 1.
 Read the following Salutation to the Dawn.
 It is a beautiful passage from the Sanskrit.
 Read it aloud in a falsetto voice to develop brightness.
 (See Voice Exercise,
 Chapter VII.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
footnotetext{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Look to this day,
 for it is life-the very life of life.
 In its brief course lie all the verities and realities of your existence:
 the bliss of growth,
 the glory of action,
 the splendor of beauty.
 Yesterday is already a dream,
 and to-morrow is only a vision;
 but to-day,
 well lived,
 makes every yesterday a dream of happiness and every to-morrow a vision of hope.
 Look,
 well,
 therefore to this day.
 Such is the salutation of the dawn.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 2.
 Read this aloud now in your natural voice,
 using the tip of the tongue to strike off the emphatic ideas with a light elastic touch.
 (See Voice Exercise,
 Chapter VI.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3.
 Take a deep breath from the diaphragm,
 and with an open and relaxed throat,
 say 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

ah.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Say it without any effort.
 Say it with perfect ease.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4.
 Turn to the Voice Exercise,
 Chapter VII,
 and read aloud with bright and happy tones,
 the four verses beginning:
