\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And with a magic tongue through it all,
 he whipped up their feelings,
 stirred their emotions,
 aroused their pity,
 heated their anger.
 Antony's masterpiece of tact and eloquence is given here in its entirety.
 Search where you will,
 range through all the broad fields of literature and oratory,
 and I doubt if you will find half a dozen speeches to equal this.
 It merits the serious study of every man who aspires to excel in the fine art of influencing
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 human nature.
 But there is another reason,
 entirely aside from the one we are considering now,
 why Shakespeare ought to be read and reread by business men;
 he possessed a larger vocabulary than did any other writer who ever lived;
 he used words more magically,
 more beautifully.
 No one can study Macbeth and Hamlet and Julius Cæsar without unconsciously brightening and widening and refining his own diction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ant.
 Friends,
 Romans,
 countrymen,
 lend me your ears:
 I come to bury Cæsar,
 not to praise him.
 The evil that men do lives after them;
 The good is oft interred with their bones:
 So let it be with Cæsar.
 The noble Brutus Hath told you Cæsar was ambitious:
 If it were so,
 it was a grievous fault;
 And grievously hath Cæsar answer'd it.
 Here,
 under leave of Brutus and the rest,For Brutus is an honorable man;
 So are they all,
 all honorable men,Come I to speak in Cæsar's funeral.
 He was my friend,
 faithful and just to me:
 But Brutus says he was ambitious;
 And Brutus is an honorable man.
 He hath brought many captives home to Rome,
 Whose ransoms did the general coffers fill:
 Did this in Cæsar seem ambitious?
 When that the poor have cried,
 Cæsar hath wept:
 Ambition should be made of sterner stuff:
 Yet Brutus says he was ambitious;
 And Brutus is an honorable man.
 You all did see that on the Lupercal I thrice presented him a kingly crown,
 Which he did thrice refuse.
 Was this ambition?
 Yet Brutus says he was ambitious;
 And,
 sure,
 he is an honorable man.
 I speak not to disprove what Brutus spoke.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But here I am,
 to speak what I do know.
 You all did love him once,-not without cause;
 What cause withholds you,
 then,
 to mourn for him?
 O judgment,
 thou art fled to brutish beasts,
 And men have lost their reason!
 Bear with me;
 My heart is in the coffin there with Cæsar,
 And I must pause till it come back to me.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I Cit.
 Methinks there is much reason in his sayings.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2 Cit.
 If thou consider rightly of the matter,
 Cæsar has had great wrong.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3 Cit.
 Has he not,
 masters?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I fear there will a worse come in his place.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4 Cit.
 Mark'd ye his words?
 He would not take the crown;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Therefore 'tis certain he was not ambitious.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I Cit.
 If it be found so,
 some will dear abide it.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2 Cit.
 Poor soul!
 his eyes are red as fire with weeping.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3 Cit.
 There's not a nobler man in Rome than Antony.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4 Cit.
 Now mark him;
 he begins again to speak.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Ant.
 But yesterday the word of Cæsar might
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Have stood against the world:
 now lies he there,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 And none so poor to do him reverence.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 O masters,
 if I were dispos'd to stir
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Your hearts and minds to mutiny and rage,
 I should do Brutus wrong,
 and Cassius wrong,
 Who,
 you all know,
 are honorable men.
 I will not do them wrong:
 I rather choose To wrong the dead,
 to wrong myself,
 and you,
 Than I will wrong such honorable men.
 But here's a parchment with the seal of Cæsar,I found it in his closet,-'tis his will:
 Let but the commons hear this testament (Which,
 pardon me,
 I do not mean to read),
 And they would go and kiss dead Cæsar's wounds,
 And dip their napkins in his sacred blood;
 Yea,
 beg a hair of him for memory,
 And,
 dying,
 mention it within their wills,
 Bequeathing it as a rich legacy Unto their issue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4 Cit.
 We'll hear the will;
 read it,
 Mark Antony.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Citizens.
 The will,
 the will!
 We will hear Cæsar's will.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Ant.
 Have patience,
 gentle friends;
 I must not read it:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 It is not meet you know how Cæsar lov'd you.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 You are not wood,
 you are not stones,
 but men;
 And,
 being men,
 hearing the will of Cæsar,
 It will inflame you,
 it will make you mad.
 'Tis good you know not that you are his heirs;
 For,
 if you should,
 O what would come of it!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4 Cit.
 Read the will!
 we'll hear it,
 Antony;
 You shall read us the will-Cæsar's will!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ant.
 Will you be patient?
 will you stay awhile?
 I have o'ershot myself,
 to tell you of it.
 I fear I wrong the honorable men Whose daggers have stabb'd Cæsar;
 I do fear it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4 Cit.
 They were traitors:
 honorable men!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Citizens.
 The will!
 the testament!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2 Cit.
 They were villains,
 murderers.
 The will!
 read the will!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ant.
 You will compel me,
 then,
 to read the will?
 Then make a ring about the corpse of Cæsar,
 And let me show you him that made the will.
 Shall I descend?
 and will you give me leave?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Citizens.
 Come down.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2 Cit.
 Descend.
