 You shall have leave.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4 Cit.
 A ring!
 stand round.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I Cit.
 Stand from the hearse;
 stand from the body.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2 Cit.
 Room for Antony!-most noble Antony!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Ant.
 Nay,
 press not so upon me;
 stand far off.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Citizens.
 Stand back;
 room!
 bear back.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Ant.
 If you have tears,
 prepare to shed them now.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 You all do know this mantle:
 I remember
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 The first time ever Cæsar put it on;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 'Twas on a summer's evening,
 in his tent,
 That day he overcame the Nervii.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Look,
 in this place ran Cassius' dagger through:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 See what a rent the envious Casca made:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Through this the well-beloved Brutus stabb'd;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And,
 as he pluck'd his cursed steel away,
 Mark how the blood of Cæsar follow'd it,As rushing out of doors,
 to be resolv'd If Brutus so unkindly knock'd,
 or no;
 For Brutus,
 as you know,
 was Cæsar's angel:
 Judge,
 O you gods,
 how dearly Cæsar lov'd him!
 This was the most unkindest cut of all;
 For,
 when the noble Cæsar saw him stab,
 Ingratitude,
 more strong than traitors' arms,
 Quite vanquish'd him:
 then burst his mighty heart;
 And,
 in his mantle muffling up his face,
 Even at the base of Pompey's statua,
 Which all the while ran blood,
 great Cæsar fell.
 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

,
 what a fall was there,
 my countrymen!
 Then I,
 and you,
 and all of us fell down,
 Whilst bloody treason flourish'd over us.
 O,
 now you weep;
 and,
 I perceive,
 you feel The dint of pity:
 these are gracious drops.
 Kind souls,
 what,
 weep you,
 when you but behold Our Cæsar's vesture wounded?
 Look you here,
 Here is himself,
 marr'd,
 as you see,
 with traitors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1 Cit.
 O piteous spectacle!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

