 2 Cit.
 We will be reveng'd.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Citizens.
 Revenge,-about,-seek,-burn;-fire,-kill,–slay,-let not a traitor live!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ant.
 Stay,
 countrymen.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 1 Cit.
 Peace there!
 hear the noble Antony.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2 Cit.
 We'll hear him,
 we'll follow him,
 we'll die with him.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Ant.
 Good friends,
 sweet friends,
 let me not stir you up To such a sudden flood of mutiny.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 They that have done this deed are honorable:
 What private griefs they have,
 alas,
 I know not,
 That made them do 't;
 they're wise and honorable,
 And will,
 no doubt,
 with reasons answer you.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I come not,
 friends,
 to steal away your hearts:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I am no orator,
 as Brutus is;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 But,
 as you know me all,
 a plain blunt man,
 That love my friend;
 and that they know full well
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 That gave me public leave to speak of him.
 For I have neither wit,
 nor words,
 nor worth,
 Action,
 nor utterance,
 nor the power of speech,
 To stir men's blood:
 I only speak right on;
 I tell you that which you yourselves do know;
 Show you sweet Cæsar's wounds,
 poor,
 poor dumb mouths,
 And bid them speak for me:
 but were I Brutus,
 And Brutus Antony,
 there were an Antony Would ruffle up your spirit,
 and put a tongue In every wound of Cæsar,
 that should move The stones of Rome to rise and mutiny.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Citizens.
 We'll mutiny.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I Cit.
 We'll burn the house of Brutus.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3 Cit.
 Away,
 then!
 come,
 seek the conspirators.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Ant.
 Yet hear me,
 countrymen;
 yet hear me speak.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Citizens.
 Peace,
 ho!
 hear Antony;
 most noble Anrony.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Ant.
 Why,
 friends,
 you go to do you know not what.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wherein hath Cæsar thus deserv'd your loves?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Alas,
 you know not;
 I must tell you,
 then:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 You have forgot the will I told you of.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Gitizens.
 Most true;
 the will!-let's stay,
 and hear the will.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Ant.
 Here is the will,
 and under Cæsar's seal.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 To every Roman citizen he gives.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 To every several man,
 seventy-five drachmas.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2 Cit.
 Most noble Cæsar!-we'll revenge his death.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3 Cit.
 O,
 royal Cæsar!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Ant.
 Hear me with patience.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Citizens.
 Peace,
 ho!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Ant.
 Moreover,
 he hath left you all his walks,
 His private arbors,
 and new-planted orchards,
 On this side Tiber;
 he hath left them you,
 And to your heirs for ever;
 common pleasures,
 To walk abroad,
 and recreate yourselves.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Here was a Cæsar!
 when comes such another?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1 Cit.
 Never,
 never-Come,
 away,
 away!
 We'll burn his body in the holy place,
 And with the brands fire the traitors' houses.
 Take up the body.
\end_layout

