\begin_layout Section*
SUMMARY
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Begin on common ground.
 Get everyone agreeing with you at the outset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Don't state your case so that people will be saying 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

no,
 no
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 at the start.
 When a person once says 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

no
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 his pride demands that he stick to it.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The more 'yesses' we can,
 at the very outset,
 induce,
 the more likely we are to succeed in capturing the attention for the ultimate proposal.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Do not begin by saying that you are going to prove so and so.
 That is liable to arouse opposition.
 Your hearers may say 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

let's see you do it.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Raise some pertinent question,
 and let them go with you in a hunt for the answer.
 .
 .
 .
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The best argument is that which seems merely an explanation.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The most famous speech that Shakespeare ever wrote is Mark Antony's funeral oration over Cæsar.
 It is a classic example of supreme tact.
 The Roman populace is friendly to the conspirators.
 Note how adroitly Antony turns this friendliness into a fury of hate.
 Note that he does it without arguing.
 He presents the facts,
 and lets them form their own opinions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SPEECH BUILDING
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
WORDS OFTEN MISPRONOUNCED
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Even in a speaker of recognized ability,
 his mispronunciations fall harshly upon the ear and cause the hearers to suspect that his early,
 if not his later,
 education,
 has been wanting in polish;
 or (what is,
 perhaps,
 more to his detriment) that he has not been accustomed to the society of refined and cultivated people.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

W.
 H.
 P.
 Phyfe.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do you sound the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 's capicalized in the following as the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in arm?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Aunt drAma heArth 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do you sound all the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 's capitalized in the following words as you sound the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in soda and sofa,
 and as you should sound the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in ask?
 Few do.
 This first shade-vowel sound of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is difficult to describe on paper.
 It is not the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in hat;
 neither is it the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in arm.
 It is between them.
 However,
 if one must err,
 it had better be in under-doing rather than in over-doing it.
 At all hazards,
 avoid anything that smacks of affectation.
 Isn't it far better,
 at least in the United States,
 to mispronounce the a in bath and half,
 giving it the sound of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in cat,
 rather than to go to the other extreme and use the sound of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 as in arm?
\end_layout

