\begin_layout Section*
ERRORS IN ENGLISH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Review.
 There are four mistakes in the following paragraph.
 Can you find them?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The president and myself,
 as officers,
 sign all checks.
 He and me were the ones who organized it and know all about the company.
 As the president often said,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

It is our company and no one understands its affairs as well as us,
 We should reap the benefits of it.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New Study Material.
 Rule:
 The various forms of the verb to be-am,
 is,
 are,
 was,
 were,
 has been,
 can be,
 could be,
 will be,
 shall be,
 would be,
 should be,
 may be-are followed by the nominative case.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 If you were 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

,
 what would you say?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 If you were 
\begin_inset Formula $me$
\end_inset

,
 what would you say?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 It was 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 that telephoned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 It was me that telephoned.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 If I was (or were) he,
 I would study at night.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 If I was him,
 I would study at night.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 I thought it was she.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 I thought it was her.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 It is we who are to blame.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 It is 
\begin_inset Formula $us$
\end_inset

 who are to blame.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 There are seemingly two exceptions to the first rule given above.
 When it precedes to be or to have been,
 the verb form is followed by the objective case of the pronoun.
 Other subjects may be used like the word 
\begin_inset Formula $it$
\end_inset

 in such construction.
 Examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 I know it to be her.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 I know it to be she.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 I know Mary to be her.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 I know Mary to be she.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 She supposed it to have been them.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 She supposed it to have been they.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 She supposed the robbers to have been them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 She supposed the robbers to have been they.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 If to be or to have been do not have it immediately in front of them,
 the verb form is followed by the nominative case of the pronoun just the same as in the first rule in this lesson.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 It was believed to be she.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 It was believed to be her.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 It was supposed to have been they.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 It was supposed to have been them.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Sometimes the subject of the principal
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 verb of the sentence is the same as the one used wich to be or to have been.
 In this instance,
 the infinitive form is followed by the nominative case.
 Examples are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Mary was believed to be she.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Mary was believed to be her.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 Mary was supposed to have been she.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Mary was supposed to have been her.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Who is used to refer to persons only.
 Which is used to refer to animals and objects.
 That may be used to refer to persons,
 animals,
 or objects.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 The only three who discussed the matter with me were very angry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 The only three which discussed the matter with me were very angry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Every customer with whom I talked.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Every customer with which I talked.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 The dog which (or that) won first prize was sold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 The dog who won first prize was sold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Affected-Effected.
 Affect mean to influence;
 as,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The market was affected by the news.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Effect means to accomplish or bring to pass;
 as,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

He effected a satisfactory settlement of the dispute.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Emigrant-Immigrant.
 When a red-whiskered and clay-piped hostler from Dublin lands at Ellis Island,
 he is an emigrant from Ireland and an immigrant to the United States.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Empty-Vacant.
 That which contains nothing
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 is empty;
 that which is without its regular occupant is vacant.
 An empty pew may not be vacant,
 and a vacant pew may not be empty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Enthuse.
 This word is not in good use.
 (Wrong) 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

His talk enthused the sales force.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Say:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

His talk made the sales force enthusiastic.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even-Exact.
 Do not use even when you mean exact.
 Say 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

An exact (not an even) dozen.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eager-Earnest-Anxious.
 Eager is more superficial and impatient and less permanent than earnest.
 Anxious suggests mental distress and possibility of disappointment.
 One may be eager to send his mother a bouquet of flowers,
 earnestly hope that the investments she has made will provide for her comfort and be anxious about her health.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-FLEXIBILITY OF THE LIPS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nervous tension-and the beginning speaker is almost always troubled with it,
 especially at the out set of his talk-is very liable to manifest itself by tightening the muscles of the throat,
 and stiffening the jaws and lips.
 We have dealt in previous chapters with directions for the relaxation of the throat and jaw.
 Let us turn our attention now to stiff,
 inflexible lips.
 They are a handicap,
 a liability.
 The lips ought to be free and flexible to aid in the molding of clear and beautiful tones.
 You can possess this additional attractiveness and carrying power in your tones,
 if you are willing to pay for it with attention and practise.
 All we can do is to write the prescription here;
 you must take the medicine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take the phrase 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

no man.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As you say no,
 round and protrude your lips.
 As you say man,
 draw them back as far as possible.
 Exaggerate the action.
 Draw them into something like a broad grin.
 Imagine that you are posing for one of those smiles you see in the advertisements for tooth paste.
 Now say it rapidly over and over:
 Mo man,
 no man,
 no man,
 no man.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Add another phrase and try it again:
 No man,
 no mind,
 no man,
 no mind,
 no man,
 no mind,
 no man,
 no mind,
 no man,
 no mind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Repeat the following sentences many times,
 exaggerating the motion of your lips,
 using them as much as you can:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So-we-do-see-across-the-lea.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Make a note of it and say I met the ice man drinking oil and selling booze.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I say turn loose the nice cats and let them eat the fat and saucy rats.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ah,
 get nice ice and bathe his foot in boiling oil.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 The open sea lures the gulls and calls to me.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Review Exercise.
 I.
 Surrender your jaw,
 let it fall like a dead weight from your head.
 Take in a deep breath,
 feel as if you were sucking the air down into your stomach,
 and chant 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

ah
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with ease,
 without one tiny trace of effort.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2.
 Take a deep breath again and say with a sweeping gesture of the hand,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I am at ease.
 My jaw is relaxed.
 My throat is open and there is no strain anywhere.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3.
 Take in a deep breath,
 and,
 using all the principles we have learned so far about diaphragmatic breathing,
 relaxation,
 breath control,
 count as
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 far as you can on one breath.
 Be sure to control the flow of the breath at the only place where it can be controlled without interfering with the voice,
 at the diaphragm.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4.
 Repeat in a falsetto voice (see Chapter VII) the following quotation from Elizabeth Barrett Browning.
 Even though you are using the ridiculous falsetto,
 try to put into the reading of this the spirit that must have moved the famous poetess to write it.
 Read it over until you yourself feel the meaning of it.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Nothing is small!
 no lily-muffled hum of summerbee but finds some coupling with the shining stars;
 no pebble at your feet but proves a sphere;
 no chaffinch but implies the cherubim.
 Earth is crammed with Heaven,
 and every common bush afire with God,
 but only he who sees takes off his shoes.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CHAPTER XI
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 HOW TO CLOSE A TALK
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The conclusion,
 too,
 has definite work to perform.
 It rounds out the talk;
 it hold's the audience's earnest attention for a brief moment on the speech as a whole.
 It draws the thread of thought together;
 it binds and finishes the fabric of the speech.
 .
 .
 .
 Definitely plan and word your conclusion.
 Never break off your speech awkwardly and hurriedly with a mumbled:
 'I guess that's all I have to say.' Complete your task and let the audience know it is complete.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 -Platform Speaking by George Rowland Collins.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The clock has nothing to do with the length of a sermon.
 Nothing whatever!
 .
 .
 .
 A long sermon is a sermon that seems long.
 .
 .
 .
 And the short sermon is the one that ends while people are still wishing for more.
 It may have lasted only twenty minutes or it may have lasted for an hour and a half.
 If it leaves the people wishing for more,
 they do not know nor care what the clock said about the length of it.
 You cannot tell,
 therefore,
 how long a sermon is by watching the hands of a clock-watch the people.
 See where their hands are.
 If the hands of the men are for the most part in their vest pockets,
 pulling out their watches to note again how long you have been at it,
 this is ominous.
 See where their eyes are!
 See where their minds are,
 then you will know exactly what time of day it is for that particular sermon.
 It may be high time for it to come to an end.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

The Art of Preaching,
 by Charles R.
 Brown,
 Dean of the Divinity School,
 Yale University.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CHAPTER XI
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
HOW TO CLOSE A TALK
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Would you like to know in what parts of your speech you are most likely to reveal your inexperience or your expertness,
 your inaptitude or your finesse?
 I'll tell you:
 in the opening and the closing.
 There is an old saying in the theater,
 referring,
 of course,
 to actors,
 that goes like this:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

By their entrances and their exits shall ye know them.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beginning and the ending!
 They are the hardest things in almost any activity to manage adroitly.
 For example,
 at a social function aren't the most trying feats the graceful entrance and the graceful leave-taking?
 In a business interview,
 aren't the most difficult tasks the winning approach and the successful close?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The close,
 is really the most strategic point in a speech;
 what one says last,
 the final words left ringing in the ears when one ceases-these are likely to be remembered longest.
 Beginners,
 however,
 seldom appreciate the importance of this coign of vantage.
 Their endings often leave much to be desired.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What are their most common errors?
 Let us discuss a few and search for remedies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First,
 there is the man who finishes with:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

That is about all I have to say on the matter;
 so I guess
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I shall stop.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 That is not an ending.
 That is a mistake.
 That reeks of the amateur.
 That is almost unpardonable.
 If that is all you have to say,
 why not round off your talk,
 and promptly take your seat and stop without talking about stopping.
 Do that,
 and the inference that that is all you have to say may,
 with safety and good taste,
 be left to the discernment of the audience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then there is the speaker who says all he has to say,
 but he does not know how to stop.
 I believe it was Josh Billings who advised people to take the bull by the tail instead of the horns,
 since it would be easier to let go.
 This speaker has the bull by the frontal extremities,
 and wants to part company with him,
 but try as hard as he will,
 he can't get near a friendly fence or tree.
 So he finally thrashes about in a circle,
 covering the same ground,
 repeating himself,
 leaving a bad impression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remedy?
 An ending has to be planned some time,
 doesn't it?
 Is it the part of wisdom to try to do it after you are facing an audience,
 while you are under the strain and stress of talking,
 while your mind must be intent on what you are saying?
 Or does common sense suggest the advisability of doing it quietly,
 calmly,
 beforehand?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even such accomplished speakers as Webster,
 Bright,
 Gladstone,
 with their admirable command of the English language,
 felt it necessary to write down and all but memorize the exact words of their closings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beginner,
 if he follows in their footsteps,
 will seldom have cause to regret it.
 He ought to know very definitely with what ideas he is going
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 to close.
 He ought to rehearse the ending several times,
 using not necessarily the same phraseology during each repetition,
 but putting the thoughts definitely into words.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An extemporaneous talk,
 during the process of delivery,
 sometimes has to be altered very materially,
 has to be cut and slashed to meet unforeseen developments,
 to harmonize with the reactions of one's hearers;
 so it is really wise to have two or three closings planned.
 If one does not fit,
 another may.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some speakers never get to the end at all.
 Along in the middle of their journey,
 they begin to sputter and misfire like an engine when the gasoline supply is about exhausted;
 after a few desperate lunges,
 they come to a complete standstill,
 a breakdown.
 They need,
 of course,
 better preparation,
 more prac-tise-more gasoline in the tank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many novices stop too abruptly.
 Their method of closing lacks smoothness,
 lacks finish.
 Properly speaking,
 they have no close;
 they merely cease suddenly,
 jerkily.
 The effect is unpleasant,
 amateurish.
 It is as if a friend in a social conversation were to break off brusquely and dart out of the room without a graceful leave-taking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No less a speaker than Lincoln made that mistake in the original draft of his First Inaugural.
 That speech was delivered at a tense time.
 The black storm clouds of dissension and hatred were already milling overhead.
 A few weeks later,
 the cyclone of blood and destruction burst upon the nation.
 Lincoln,
 addressing his closing words to the people of the South,
 had intended to end in this fashion:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

In your hands,
 my dissatisfied fellow-countrymen,
 and not in mine,
 is the momentous issue of the civil war.
 The government will not assail you.
 You can have no conflict without being yourselves the aggressors.
 You have no oath registered in heaven to destroy the government,
 while I have a most solemn one to preserve,
 protect and defend it.
 You can forbear the assault upon it.
 I cannot shrink from the defense of it.
 With you and not with me is the solemn question of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Shall it be peace or a sword?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He submitted his speech to Secretary Seward.
 Seward quite appropriately pointed out that the ending was too blunt,
 too abrupt,
 too provocative.
 So Seward himself tried his hand at a closing;
 in fact,
 he wrote two.
 Lincoln accepted one of them and used it,
 with slight modifications,
 in place of the last three sentences of the close he had originally prepared.
 The result was that his First Inaugural Address now lost its provocative abruptness and rose to a climax of friendliness,
 of sheer beauty and poetical eloquence:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I am loth to close.
 We are not enemies but friends.
 We must not be enemies.
 Though passion may have strained,
 it must not break our bonds of affection.
 The mystic chords of memory,
 stretching from every battlefield and patriot's grave to every living heart and hearthstone all over this broad land,
 will swell the chorus of the Union when again touched,
 as surely they will be,
 by the better angel of our nature.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How can a beginner develop the proper feeling for the close of an address?
 By mechanical rules?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No.
 Like culture,
 it is too delicate for that.
 It must be a matter of sensing,
 almost of intuition.
 Unless a speaker can feel when it is done har-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 moniously,
 adroitly,
 how can he himself hope to do it?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 this feeling can be cultivated;
 this expertness can be developed somewhat,
 by studying the ways in which accomplished speakers have achieved it.
 Here is an illustration,
 the close of an address by the then Prince of Wales before the Empire Club of Toronto:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I am afraid,
 gentlemen,
 that I have departed from my reserve,
 and talked about myself a good deal too much.
 But I wanted to tell you,
 as the largest audience that I have been privileged to address in Canada,
 what I feel about my position and the responsibility which it entails.
 I can only assure you that I shall always endeavor to live up to that great responsibility and to be worthy of your trust.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A blind man listening to that talk would feel that it was ended.
 It isn't left dangling in the air like a loose rope.
 It isn't left ragged and jagged.
 It is rounded off,
 it is finished.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The famous Dr.
 Harry Emerson Fosdick spoke in the Geneva Cathedral of St.
 Pierre the Sunday after the opening of the sixth assembly of the League of Nations.
 He chose for his text:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

All they that take the sword shall perish with the sword.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note the beautiful and lofty and powerful way in which he brought his sermon to a close:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
footnotetext{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

We cannot reconcile Jesus Christ and war-that is the essence of the matter.
 That is the challenge which to-day should stir the conscience of Christendom.
 War is the most colossal and ruinous social sin that afflicts mankind;
 it is utterly and irremediably unchristian;
 in its total method and effect it means everything that Jesus did not 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 mean and it means nothing that he did mean;
 it is a more blatant denial of every Christian doctrine about God and man than all the theoretical atheists on earth ever could devise.
 It would be worth while,
 would it not,
 to see the Christian Church claim as her own this greatest moral issue of our time,
 to see her lift once more as in our fathers' days,
 a clear standard against the paganism of this present world and,
 refusing to hold her conscience at the beck and call of belligerent states,
 put the kingdom of God above nationalism and call the world to peace?
 That would not be the denial of patriotism but its apotheosis.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Here to-day,
 as an American,
 under this high and hospitable roof,
 I cannot speak for my government,
 but both as an American and as a Christian I do speak for millions of my fellow citizens in wishing your great work,
 in which we believe,
 for which we pray,
 our absence from which we painfully regret,
 the eminent success which it deserves.
 We work in many ways for the same end-a world organized for peace.
 Never was an end better worth working for.
 The alternative is the most appalling catastrophe mankind has ever faced.
 Like gravitation in the physical realm,
 the law of the Lord in the moral realm bends for no man and no nation:
 'All they that take the sword shall perish with the sword.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But this collection of speech endings would not be complete without the majestic tones,
 the organlike melody of the close of Lincoln's Second Inaugural.
 The late Earl Curzon,
 of Keddleston,
 Chancellor of Oxford University,
 declared that this selection was 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

