\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 If you will go to the public library in your town and tell the librarian that you are preparing a talk on a certain subject and that you wish a poetical quotation to express this idea or that,
 she may be able to help you find something suitable in some reference volume such as Bartlett's book of quotations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
THE POWER OF A BIBLICAL QUOTATION
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you can quote a passage from Holy Writ to back up your speech,
 you are fortunate.
 A choice Biblical quotation often has a profound effect.
 The well known financier,
 Frank Vanderlip,
 used this method in ending his address on the Allied Debts to the United States:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

If we insist to the letter upon our claim,
 our claim will in all probability never be met.
 If we insist upon it selfishly,
 we realize in hatreds but not in cash.
 If we are generous,
 and wisely generous,
 those claims can all be paid,
 and the good we do with them will mean more to us materially than anything we would conceivably be parting with.
 'For whosoever will save his life shall lose it;
 but whosoever shall lose his life for My sake and the Gospel's,
 the same shall save it.' 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
THE CLIMAX
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The climax is a popular way of ending.
 It is often difficult to manage and is not an ending for
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 all speakers nor for all subjects.
 But,
 when wull done,
 it is excellent.
 It works up to a crest,
 a weak,
 getting stronger sentence by sentence.
 A good illustration of the climax will be found in the close of the prize winning speech on Philadelphia in Chapter III.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lincoln used the climax in preparing his notes for a lecture on Niagara Falls.
 Note how each comparison is stronger than the preceding,
 how he gets a cumulative effect by comparing its age to Columbus,
 Christ,
 Moses,
 Adam,
 and so on:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

It calls up the indefinite past.
 When Columbus first sought this continent-when Christ suffered on the crosswhen Moses led Israel through the Red Sea-nay,
 even when Adam first came from the hands of his Maker;
 then,
 as now,
 Niagara was roaring here.
 The eyes of that species of extinct giants whose bones fill the mounds of America have gazed on Niagara,
 as ours do now.
 Contemporary with the first race of men,
 and older than the first man,
 Niagara is as strong and fresh to-day as ten thousand years ago.
 The Mammoth and Mastodon,
 so long dead that fragments of their monstrous bones alone testify that they ever lived,
 have gazed on Niagara-in that long,
 long time never still for a moment,
 never dried,
 never frozen,
 never slept,
 never rested.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wendell Phillips employed this selfsame technique in his address on Toussaint l'Ouverture.
 The close of it is quoted below.
 This selection is often cited in books on public speaking.
 It has vigor,
 vitality.
 It is interesting even though it is a bit too ornate for this practical age.
 This speech was written more than half a century ago.
 Amusing,
 isn't it,
 to note how woefully wrong were Wendell Phillips' prognostications concerning the historical
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 significance of John Brown and Toussaint l'Ouverture 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

fifty years hence when truth gets a hearing
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

?
 It is as hard evidently to guess history as it is to foretell next year's stock market or the price of lard.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I would call him Napoleon,
 but Napoleon made his way to empire over broken oaths and through a sea of blood.
 This man never broke his word.
 'No Retaliation' was his great motto and the rule of his life;
 and the last words uttered to his son in France were these:
 'My boy,
 you will one day go back to Santo Domingo;
 forget that France murdered your father.' I would call him Cromwell,
 but Cromwell was only a soldier,
 and the state he founded went down with him into his grave.
 I would call him Washington,
 but the great Virginian held slaves.
 This man risked his empire rather than permit the slave-trade in the humblest village of his dominions.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

You think me a fanatic to-night,
 for you read history,
 not with your eyes,
 but with your prejudices.
 But fifty years hence,
 when Truth gets a hearing,
 the Muse of History will put Phocion for the Greek,
 and Brutus for the Roman,
 Hampden for England,
 Lafayette for France,
 choose Washington as the bright,
 consummate flower of our earlier civilization,
 and John Brown the ripe fruit of our noonday,
 then,
 dipping her pen in the sunlight,
 will write in the clear blue,
 above them all,
 the name of the soldier,
 the statesman,
 the martyr,
 Toussaint L'Ouverture.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
WHEN THE TOE TOUCHES
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hunt,
 search,
 experiment until you get a good ending and a good beginning.
 Then get them close together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The speaker who does not cut his talk to fit in with the prevailing mood of this hurried,
 rapid age will be unwelcome and,
 sometimes,
 positively dis liked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No less a saint than Saul of Tarsus sinned in this respect.
 He preached until a chap in the audience,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

a young man named Eutychus,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 went to sleep and fell out of a window and all but broke his neck.
 Even then he may not have stopped talking.
 Who knows?
 I remember a speaker,
 a doctor,
 standing up one night at the University Club,
 Brooklyn.
 It had been a long banquet.
 Many speakers had already talked.
 It was two o'clock in the morning when his turn came.
 Had he been endowed with tact and fine feeling and discretion,
 he would have said half a dozen sentences and let us go home.
 But did he?
 No,
 not he.
 He launched into a forty-five minute tirade against vivisection.
 Long before he was half way through his audience were wishing that he,
 like Eutychus,
 would fall out of a window and break something,
 anything,
 to silence him.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mr.
 Lorimer,
 the editor of the Saturday Evening Post,
 told me that he always stopped a series of articles in the Post when they were at the height of their popularity,
 and people were clamoring for more.
 Why stop then?
 Why then of all times?
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Because,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 said Mr.
 Lorimer-and he ought to know-
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

the point of satiation is reached very soon after that peak of popularity.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same wisdom will apply,
 and ought to be applied,
 to speaking.
 Stop while the audience is still eager to have you go on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The greatest speech Christ ever delivered,
 the Sermon on the Mount,
 can be repeated in five minutes.
 Lincoln's Gettysburg address has only ten sentences.
 One can read the whole story of crea-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 tion in Genesis in less time than it takes to peruse a murder story in the morning paper.
 .
 .
 .
 Be brief!
 Be brief!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Doctor Johnson,
 Archdeacon of Nyasa,
 has written a book about the primitive peoples of Africa.
 He has lived among them,
 observed them,
 for forty-nine years.
 He relates that when a speaker talks too long at a village gathering or the Gwangwara,
 the audience silences him with shouts of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Imetosha!
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Imetosha!
