\begin_layout Standard
Another tribe is said to permit a speaker to hold forth only so long as he can stand on one foot.
 When the toe of the lifted member touches the ground,
 finito.
 He has come to an end.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And the average white audience,
 even though they are more polite,
 more restrained,
 dislike long speeches as much as do those African negroes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 So be warned by their lot,
 Which I know you will not,
 And learn about speaking from them.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SUMMARY
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I.
 The close of a speech is really its most strategic element.
 What is said last is likely to be remembered longest.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2.
 Do not end with:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

That is about all I have to say on the matter ;
 so I guess I shall stop.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Stop,
 but don't talk about stopping.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3.
 Plan your ending carefully in advance as Webster,
 Bright,
 and Gladstone did.
 Rehearse.
 Know almost word for word how you are going to close.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Round off your talk.
 Don't leave it rough and broken like a jagged rock.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4.
 Seven suggested ways of closing:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 a.
 Summarizing,
 restating,
 outlining briefly the main points you have covered.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 b.
 Appealing for action.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 c.
 Paying the audience a sincere compliment.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 d.
 Raising a laugh.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 e.
 Quoting a fitting verse of poetry.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 f.
 Using a Biblical quotation.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 g.
 Building up a climax.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 5.
 Get a good ending and a good beginning;
 and get them close together.
 Always stop before your audience wants you to.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The point of satiation is reached very soon after the peak of popularity。

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
SPEECH BUILDING
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
WORDS OFTEN MISPRONOUNCED
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $o$
\end_inset

 in comely,
 and the capitalized 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{\prime}s$
\end_inset

 in sUpple,
 sUburban and IUscious are sounded as 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The letters capitalized in the following should be sounded,
 not as the 
\begin_inset Formula $oo$
\end_inset

 in ooze,
 but as the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in futility and music.
 This,
 the long 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 sound,
 consists of a close union of the sound of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $it$
\end_inset

,
 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $oo$
\end_inset

 in ooze.
 The precise sounding of the long 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}$
\end_inset

 is rare and is an infallible sign of cultured pronunciation.
 In a few words,
 it is always enunciated correctly.
 For example,
 we never say moosic for music,
 foo for few,
 food for feud,
 footure for future,
 boogle for bugle,
 or coopid for cupid;
 but how many of us say noo for new,
 dooty for duty,
 and Toosday for Tuesday!
\end_layout

