\begin_layout Section*
ERRORS IN ENGLISH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Review.
 There are four mistakes in the following paragraph.
 See if you can discover them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which was the man who did the deed?
 The evidence all pointed to Mr.
 Watson.
 I thought it to be he but it was supposed by the others to have been them who escaped in the night.
 In the long run,
 it was us who were wrong in both cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New Study Material.
 Rule:
 When a pronoun is the direct object of a verb,
 it is always in the objective case.
 In other words,
 if the verb in the sentence denotes an action that passes over to or affects the pronoun,
 then the pronoun must be in the objective case.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 He asked you and me to lunch.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 He asked you and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 to lunch.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 The manager asked her and me to do it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 The manager asked she and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 to do it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 I cannot say whom we will hire.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 (In the above sentence,
 whom is the object of the transitive verb will hire,
 and consequently the pronoun must be in the objective case.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 I cannot say who we will hire.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 A landslide hit their home,
 demolishing their house and killing both him and his wife instantly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

A landslide hit their home,
 demolishing their house and killing both he and his wife instantly.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (From an advertisement issued by the Illinois Commercial Men's Association.) (There should be another change in this sentence,
 making it read,
 in part,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

both his wife and him.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is,
 perhaps,
 a rather fine point,
 but careful speakers usually mention the lady first.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 The school graduated us and our classmates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 The school graduated we and our classmates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here,
 again,
 attention should be called to the improper use of the compounds.
 We are prone to use myself,
 yourself,
 herself,
 when we do not intend to express reflected action or emphasis.
 You recall that this was discussed in Chapter IX.
 As stated before,
 this generaily happens because we are not sure whether to use the nominative or objective form of the pronoun.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 The wrecking car brought the automobile and them back home.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 The wrecking car brought the automobile and themselves back home.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

We think by words,
 and therefore thought and words cannot but set and reset on each other.
 As a man speaks,
 so he thinks,
 and,
 'as a man thinketh in his heart,
 so he is.' 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 G.
 P.
 Marsh,
 Lectures On The English Language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Friendly-Amicable.
 Friendly is stronger and less formal than amicable.
 A man who is companionable and sociable may not be cordial and genial.
 The first two words denote manner and behavior and may be applied where no genuine feeling exists;
 the last two qualities imply a sincere and warm friendliness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generous-Liberal-Magnanimous.
 Generous means giving freely and at a sacrifice.
 Liberal refers to the amount of the gift.
 If your washerwoman gave twenty dollars to the Y.
 M.
 C.
 A.,
 it would be generous.
 If the United States Steel Corporation contributed ten millions it would be liberal.
 Magnanimous means lofty,
 noble,
 raised above what is low and mean.
 It is magnanimous of you to forgive those who have wronged you.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Healthful-Healthy.
 Healthful means promoting or preserving health;
 as,
 a healthful climate.
 Healthy means enjoying health;
 as,
 a healthy man.
 Do not speak of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

healthy food
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

healthy exercise.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Honest-Honorable.
 The honest man does not lie,
 or steal,
 or defraud;
 the honorable man takes no unfair advantage,
 and he may even willingly sacrifice for the cause of right.
 The honest man does not lie in a horse trade.
 An honorable
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 man deliberately tells you that his nag is balky on cold mornings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-DEVELOPING RESONANCE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The three fundamental principles of good tone production are correct breath control,
 relaxation and resonance.
 We have already dealt with the first two principles;
 now for the third:
 resonance.
 What is it that strengthens and beautifies the tone of your radio or victrola?
 The horn or loud speaker.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Your body acts as a sounding board for your voice much in the same way that the body of a violin or piano amplifies and beautifies the tones produced by the musician.
 The initial tone is made by the vocal chords,
 but this rises and reverberates against the hard bony structures of the chest,
 the teeth,
 the roof of the mouth,
 the nasal cavities and other parts of the face.
 This reverberation gives to the voice its most important quality.
 Think of the voice as a sky rocket rising from the diaphragm up through the darkness of your relaxed throat and breaking into a shower of sound against the nostrils and other bony parts of the head.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our problem is not to speak with insonance.
 You have been speaking with it all your life.
 You could not be heard ten feet without it.
 Our task is to speak with increased resonance.
 How shall we set about it?
 Let me quote an interesting paragraph from a volume by Fucito and Beyer,
 entitled Caruso and the Art of Singing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
footnotetext{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

A great deal has been said about the value of humming as a vocal exercise.
 .
 .
 .
 Humming,
 if correctly practised.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 will develop the resonance of the voice.
 The humming or most people sounds like a caterwaul because the jaw,
 the lips,
 the tongue and the vocal membranes are all painfully rigid.
 Of course,
 the vocal organs should be in the same position for humming as for good tone production:
 there should be complete relaxation of the facial muscles,
 the jaw,
 and the tongue,
 just as they are kept when in a state of repose or while sleeping;
 the lips are to be lightly united.
 Thus the tone vibrations will neither be deadened by obstructing muscles nor forced through the nose by the strain;
 instead they will resonate within the nasal cavities and make the notes round and beautiful.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now with relaxed tongue,
 throat,
 lips and jaw,
 let us hum the music of My Old Kentucky Home:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sun shines bright in my old Kentucky home,
 'Tis summer,
 the darkies are gay;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 The corntop's ripe,
 and the meadow's all in bloom,
 While the birds make music all the day.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 The young folks roll on the little cabin floor,
 All merry,
 all happy and bright;
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 By'n'by hard times comes a-knocking at the door,
 Then my old Kentucky home,
 good-night!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CHORUS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Weep no more,
 my lady,
 Oh!
 weep no more to-day!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 We will sing one song for the old Kentucky home,
 For the old Kentucky home,
 far away.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first time you ham this,
 put the palm of your hand on top of your head and feel the vibration there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is most important:
 in practising all these exercises for resonance,
 let your first step be the taking of a deep breath at the diaphragm and relaxing the chest and feeling it riding on the breath.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note the open feeling that you have in your face and nose and head as you drink the air in.
 As you begin to hum and exhale,
 do not think of exhaling at all.
 Imagine that you are still inhaling,
 still feeling that open sensation in the head.
 That means open cavities to reënforce and amplify your resonance.
 Cultivate this inhaling sensation in all your speaking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now hum this song once more.
 Place your hand this time on the back of your head and feel the vibration there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A third time,
 think the tone in your nose.
 Feel as if it were flowing up and into the nose-the same sensation as in inhaling.
 Hold the bony part of your nose,
 just a little below the eyes,
 with a thumb and a forefinger.
 Feel the vibration there this time as you hum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the sake of variety,
 let us hum now the tune of The Old Folks at Home:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Way down upon the Swanee River,
 Far,
 far away,
 There's where my heart is turning ever There's where the old folks stay.
 All up and down the whole creation,
 Sadly I roam,
 Still longing for the old plantation,
 And for the old folks at home.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CHORUS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the world is sad and dreary,
 Everywhere I roam,
 Oh!
 darkies,
 how my heart grows weary,
 Far from the old folks at home.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As you hum it this time,
 think it forward on the lips.
 Place your forefinger on your lips and feel them vibrate.
 They ought to vibrate until they tickle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now hum it again in as low a tone as possible;
 and,
 placing your open palm on your chest,
 feel the vibration there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hum it once more,
 keeping the palm of your right hand on your chest and moving the palm of the left over various parts of the head and face.
 Feel your whole body vibrating,
 causing resonance.
 I have known singers who,
 when they hummed,
 felt the vibrations even in their fingers and toes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Singing is a splendid voice exercise in itself;
 so,
 using all the principles of voice production discussed in these lessons,
 let us sing now these two old familiar songs that we have betn humming.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CHAPTER XII
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 HOW TO MAKE YOUR MEANING CLEAK
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Nine readers out of ten take a lucid statement for a true one.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Encyclopedia Britannica.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Study carefully what you have to say,
 and put it into words by writing or by speaking aloud to an imaginary person.
 Arrange your points in order.
 Stick to your order.
 Divide your time among your points according to their importance.
 Stop when you are through.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Dr.
 Edward Everett Hale.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

If speaking on Solomon to a group of business men,
 refer to him as the J.
 P.
 Morgan of his day.
 If talking to baseball fans about Samson call him the Babe Ruth of his time.
 When Frank Simonds undertook to describe Foch's strategy in battering down the Hindenburg line he used the figure of pounding at the two hinges of a gate.
 In a similar manner Hugo used the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to illustrate the battlefield of Waterloo,
 and Elson the horseshoe in describing the battle of Gettysburg.
 Everyone is acquainted with gates,
 horseshoes and the alphabet,
 although not everyone has seen battles.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Glenn Clark,
 Self-Cultivation in Extemporaneous Speaking.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

One picture is worth ten thousand words.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Chinese Proverb.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

My father was a man of great intellectual energy.
 My best training came from him.
 He was intolerant of vagueness,
 and from the time I began to write until his death in 1903,
 when he was eighty-one years old,
 I carried everything I wrote to him.
 He would make me read it aloud,
 which was always painful to me.
 Every now and then he would stop me.
 'What do you mean by that?' I would tell him,
 and,
 of course,
 in doing so would express myself more simply than I had on paper.
 'Why didn't you say so?' he would go on.
 'Don't shoot at your meaning with birdshot and hit the whole countryside;
 shoot with a rifle at the thing you have to say.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Woodrow Wilson.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CHAPTER XII
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
HOW TO MAKE YOUR MEANING CLEAR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A famous English bishop,
 during the war,
 spoke to some unlettered negro troops at Camp Upton,
 Long Island.
 They were on their way to the trenches;
 but a very small percentage of them had any adequate idea why they were being sent.
 I know:
 I questioned them.
 Yet the Lord Bishop talked to these negroes about 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

International amity,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Servia's right to a place in the sun.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Why,
 the half of those negroes did not know whether Servia was a town or a disease.
 He might as well,
 as far as results were concerned,
 have delivered a sonorous eulogy on the Nebular Hypothesis.
 However,
 not a single trooper left the hall while he was speaking:
 the military police with revolvers were stationed at every exit to prevent that consummation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I do not wish to belittle the bishop.
 He is every inch a scholar;
 and before a body of collegiate men he would probably have been powerful;
 but he failed with these negroes,
 and he failed utterly:
 he did not know his audience,
 and he evidently knew neither the precise purpose of his talk nor how to accomplish it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What do we mean by the purpose of an address?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just this:
 every talk,
 regardless of whether the speaker realizes it or not,
 has one of four major goals.
 What are they?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I.
 To make something clear.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2.
 To impress and convince.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3.
 To get action.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4.
 To entertain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us illustrate these by a series of concrete examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lincoln,
 who was always more or less interested in mechanics,
 once invented and patented a device for lifting stranded boats off sand bars and other obstructions.
 He worked in a mechanic's shop near his law office,
 making a model of his apparatus.
 Although the device finally came to naught,
 he was decidedly enthusiastic over its possibilities.
 When friends came to his office to view the model,
 he took no end of pains to explain it.
 The main purpose of those explanations was clearness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When he delivered his immortal oration at Gettysburg,
 when he gave his first and second inaugural addresses,
 when Henry Clay died and Lincoln delivered an eulogy on his life-on all these occasions,
 Lincoln's main purpose was impressiveness and conviction.
 He had to be clear,
 of course,
 before he could be convincing;
 but,
 in these instances,
 clearness was not his major consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In his talks to juries,
 he tried to win favorable decisions.
 In his political talks,
 he tried to win votes.
 His purpose,
 then,
 was action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two years before he was elected President,
 Lincoln prepared a lecture on Inventions.
 His pur-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 pose was entertainment.
 At least,
 that should have been his goal;
 but he was evidently not very successful in attaining it.
 His career as a popular lecturer was,
 in fact,
 a distinct disappointment.
 In one town,
 not a person came to hear him.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But he did succeed and he succeeded famously in the other speeches of his that I have referred to.
 And why?
 Because,
 in those instances,
 he knew his goal,
 and he knew how to achieve it.
 He knew where he wanted to go and how to get there.
 And because so many speakers don't know just that,
 they often flounder and come to grief.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example:
 I once saw a United States Congressman hooted and hissed and forced to leave the stage of the old New York Hippodrome,
 because he had-unconsciously,
 no doubt,
 but nevertheless,
 unwisely-chosen clearness as his goal.
 It was during the war.
 He talked to his audience about how the United States was preparing.
 The crowd did not want to be instructed.
 They wanted to be entertained.
 They listened to him patiently,
 politely,
 for ten minutes,
 a quarter of an hour,
 hoping the performance would come to a rapid end.
 But it didn't.
 He rambled on and on;
 patience snapped;
 the audience would not stand for more.
 Someone began to cheer ironically.
 Others took it up.
 In a moment,
 a thousand people were whistling and shouting.
 The speaker,
 obtuse and incapable as he was of sensing the temper of his audience,
 had the bad taste to continue.
 That aroused them.
 A battle was on.
 Their impatience mounted to ire.
 They determined to silence him.
 Louder and louder grew their storm of protest.
 Finally,
 the roar of it,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 the anger of it drowned his words-he could not have been heard twenty feet away.
 So he was forced to give up,
 acknowledge defeat,
 and retire in humiliation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Profit by his example.
 Know your goal.
 Choose it wisely before you set out to prepare your talk.
 Know how to reach it.
 Then set about it,
 doing it skillfully and with science.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All this requires knowledge,
 special and technical instruction.
 And so important is this phase of speech construction that four chapters of this course will be devoted to it.
 The remainder of this chapter will show you how to make your talks clear.
 Chapter XIII will indicate how to make them impressive and convincing.
 Chapter XIV will show how to make them interesting.
 Chapter XV will demonstrate a scientific method for getting action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
USE COMPARISONS TO PROMOTE CLEARNESS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As to clearness:
 do not underestimate the importance of it nor the difficulty.
 I recently heard a certain Irish poet give an evening of readings from his own poems.
 Not ten per cent of the audience,
 half the time,
 knew what he was talking about.
 Many talkers,
 both in public and private,
 are a lot like that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When I discussed the essentials of public speaking with Sir Oliver Lodge,
 a man who has been lecturing to university classes and to the public for forty years,
 he emphasized most of all the importance,
 first,
 of knowledge and preparation;
 second,
 of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

taking good pains to be clear.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The great General Von Moltke,
 at the outbreak of the Franco-Prussian War,
 said to his officers:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Remember,
 gentlemen,
 that any order that can be misunderstood,
 will be misunderstood.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Napoleon recognized the same danger.
 His most emphatic and oft-reiterated instruction to his secretaries was:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Be clear!
 Be clear!
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the disciples asked Christ why He taught the public by parables,
 He answered:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Because they seeing,
 see not:
 and hearing,
 hear not;
 neither do they understand.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And when you talk on a subject strange to your hearer or hearers,
 can you hope that they will anderstand you any more readily than people understood the Master?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hardly.
 So what can we do about it?
 What did He do when confronted by a similar situation?
 Solved it in the most simple and natural manner imaginable:
 described the things people did not know by likening them to things they did know.
 The kingdom of Heaven .
 .
 .
 what would it be like?
 How,
 could those untutored peasants of Palestine know?
 So Christ described it in terms of objects and actions with which they were already familiar:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The kingdom of Heaven is like unto leaven,
 which a.
 woman took,
 and hid in three measures of meal,
 till the whole was leavened.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Again,
 the kingdom of Heaven is like unto a merchantman seeking goodly pearls.
 .
 .
 .
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Again,
 the kingdom of Heaven is like unto a net that was cast into the sea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That was lucid;
 they could understand that.
 The housewives in the audience were using leaven every week;
 the fishermen were casting their nets into the sea daily;
 the merchants were dealing in pearls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And how did David make clear the watchfulness and loving kindness of Jehovah?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The Lord is my shepherd,
 I shall not want.
 He maketh me to lie down in green pastures,
 He leadeth me beside the still waters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Green grazing grounds in that almost barren country .
 .
 .
 still waters where the sheep could drink-those pastoral people could understand that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is a rather striking and half-amusing example of the use of this principle:
 some missionaries were translating the Bible into the dialect of a tribe living near equatorial Africa.
 They progressed to the verse:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Though your sins be as scarlet,
 they shall be white as snow.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 How were they to translate that?
 Literally?
 Meaningless.
 Absurd.
 The natives had never scooped off the sidewalk on a February morning.
 They did not even have a word for snow.
 They could not have told the difference between snow and coal tar;
 but they had climbed cocoanut trees many times and shaken down a few nuts for lunch;
 so the missionaries likened the unknown to the known,
 and changed the verse to read:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Though your sins be as scarlet,
 they shall be as white as the meat of a cocoanut.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the circumstances,
 it would be hard to improve on that,
 wouldn't it?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the State Teachers' College at Warrensburg,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Missouri,
 I once heard a lecturer on Alaska who failed,
 in many places,
 to be either clear or interesting because,
 unlike those African missionaries,
 he neglected to talk in terms of what his audience knew.
 He told us,
 for example,
 that Alaska had a gross area of 590,804 square miles,
 and a population of 64,356.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Half a million square miles-what does that mean to the average man?
 Precious little.
 He is not used to thinking in terms of square miles.
 They conjure up no mental picture.
 He does not have any idea whether half a million square miles are approximately the size of Maine or Texas.
 Suppose the speaker had said that the coast line of Alaska and its islands is longer than the distance around the globe,
 and that its area more than equals the combined areas of Vermont,
 New Hampshire,
 Maine,
 Massachusetts,
 Rhode Island,
 Connecticut,
 New York,
 New Jersey,
 Pennsylvania,
 Delaware,
 Maryland,
 West Virginia,
 North Carolina,
 South Carolina,
 Georgia,
 Florida,
 Mississippi and Tennessee.
 Would not that give everyone a fairly clear conception of the area of Alaska?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He said the population was 64,356 .
 The chances are that not one person in ten remembered the census figures for five minutes-or even one minute.
 Why?
 Because the rapid saying of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

sixty-four thousand,
 three hundred and fifty-six
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 does not make a very clear impression.
 It leaves only a loose,
 insecure impression,
 like words written on the sand of the seashore.
 The next wave of attention quite obliterates them.
 Would it not have been better to have stated the census in terms of some-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 thing with which they were very familiar?
 For example:
 St.
 Joseph was not very far away from that little Missouri town where the audience lived.
 Many of them had been to St.
 Joseph;
 and,
 Alaska had,
 at that time,
 ten thousand less people than St.
 Joseph.
 Better still,
 why not talk about Alaska in terms of the very town where you are speaking?
 Wouldn't the speaker have been far clearer had he said:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Alaska is eight times as large as the state of Missouri;
 yet it has only thirteen times as many people as live right here in Warrensburg
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following illustrations,
 which are the clearer,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 statement or the 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 ?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 (a) Our nearest star is thirty-five trillion miles away.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 (b) A train going at the rate of a mile a minute would reach our nearest star in forty-eight million years;
 if a song were sung there and the sound could travel here it would be three million,
 eight hundred thousand years before we could hear it.
 A spider's thread reaching to it would weigh five hundred tons.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 (a) St.
 Peter's,
 the biggest church in the world,
 is 232 yards long,
 and 364 feet wide.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 (b) It is about the size of two buildings like the capitol at Washington piled on top of one another.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sir Oliver Lodge happily uses this method when explaining the size and nature of atoms to a popular audience.
 I heard him tell a European audience that there were as many atoms in a drop of water as there were drops of water in the Mediterranean Sea ;
 and many of his hearers had spent over a week sailing from Gibraltar to the Suez Canal.
 To bring the matter still closer home,
 he said there were
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 as many atoms in one drop of water as there were blades of grass on all the earth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Richard Harding Davis told a New York audience that the Mosque of St.
 Sophia was 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

about as big as the auditorium of the Fifth Avenue theater.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 He said Brindisi 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

looks like Long Island City when you come into it from the rear.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use this principle henceforth in your talks.
 If you are describing the great pyramid,
 first tell your hearers it is 451 feet,
 then tell them how high that is in terms of scme building they see every day.
 Tell how many city blocks the base would cover.
 Don't speak about so many thousand gallons of this or so many hundred thousand barrels of that without also telling how many rooms the size of the one you are speaking in could be filled with that much liquid.
 Instead of saying twenty feet high,
 why not say one and a half times as high as this ceiling?
 Instead of talking about distance in terms of rods or miles,
 is it not clearer to say as far as from here to the union station,
 or to such and such a street?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
AVOID TECHNICAL TERMS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you belong to a profession the work of which is technical-if you are a lawyer,
 a physician,
 an engineer,
 or are in a highly specialized line of busi-ness-be doubly careful when you talk to outsiders,
 to express yourself in plain terms and to give necessary details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I say be doubly careful,
 for,
 as a part of my professional duties,
 I have listened to hundreds 
\begin_inset Formula $o^{c}$
\end_inset

 speeches that failed right at this point and failed
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 woefully.
 The speakers appeared totally unconscious of the general public's widespread and profound ignorance regarding their particular specialties.
 So what happened?
 They rambled on and on,
 uttering thoughts,
 using phrases that fitted into their experience and were instantly and continuously meaningful to them;
 but to the uninitiated,
 they were about as clear as the Missouri River after the June rains have fallen on the newly-plowed corn fields of Iowa and Kansas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What should such a speaker do?
 He ought to read and heed the following advice from the facile pen of Ex-Senator Beveridge of Indiana:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

It is a good practice to pick out the least intelligent looking person in the audience and strive to make that person interested in your argument.
 This can be done only by lucid statement of fact and clear reasoning.
 An even better method is to center your talk on some small boy or girl present with parents.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Say to yourself-say out loud to your audience,
 if you like-that you will try to be so plain that the child will understand and remember your explanation of the question discussed,
 and after the meeting be able to tell what you have said.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I remember hearing a physician,
 a student of this course,
 remark in the course of his talk that 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

diaphragmatic breathing is a distinct aid to the peristaltic action of the intestines and a boon to health.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 He was about to dismiss that phase of his talk with that one sentence and to rush on to something else.
 I stopped him;
 and asked for a show of hands of those who had a clear conception of how diaphragmatic breathing differs from other kinds of breath-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 ing,
 why it is especially beneficial to physical wellbeing and what peristaltic action is.
 The result of the vote surprised the doctor;
 so he went back,
 explained,
 enlarged in this fashion:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The diaphragm is a thin muscle forming the floor of the chest at the base of the lungs and the roof of the abdominal cavity.
 When inactive and during chest breathing,
 it is arched like an inverted washbowl.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

In abdominal breathing every breath forces this muscular arch down until it becomes nearly flat and you can feel your stomach muscles pressing against your belt.
 This downward pressure of the diaphragm massages and stimulates the organs of the upper part of the abdominal cavitythe stomach,
 the liver,
 the pancreas,
 the spleen,
 the solar plexus.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

When you breathe out again,
 your stomach and your intestines will be forced up against the diaphragm and will be given another massage.
 This massaging helps the process of elimination.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

A vast amount of ill health originates in the intestines.
 Most indigestion,
 constipation,
 and auto-intoxication would disappear if our stomachs and intestines were properly exercised through deep diaphragmatic breathing.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
THE SECRET OF LINCOLN'S CLEARNESS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lincoln had a deep and abiding affection for putting a proposition so that it would be instantly clear to everyone.
 In his first message to Congress,
 he used the phrase 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

sugar-coated.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Mr.
 Defrees,
 the public printer,
 being Lincoln's personal friend,
 suggested to him that although the phrase might be all right for a stump speech in Illinois,
 it was not dignified enough for a historical state paper.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Well,
 Defrees,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Lincoln replied,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

if you think the time
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 will ever come when the people will not understand what 'sugar-coated' means,
 I'll alter it;
 otherwise,
 I think I'll let it go.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He once explained to Dr.
 Gulliver,
 the President of Knox College,
 how he developed his 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

passion
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for plain language,
 as he phrased it:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Among my earliest recollections I remember how,
 when a mere child,
 I used to get irritated when anybody talked to me in a way I could not understand.
 I don't think I ever got angry at anything else in my life.
 But that always disturbed my temper,
 and has ever since.
 I can remember going to my little bedroom,
 after hearing the neighbors talk of an evening with my father,
 and spending no small part of the night walking up and down and trying to make out the exact meaning of some of their,
 to me,
 dark sayings.
 I could not sleep,
 though I often tried to,
 when I got on such a hunt after an idea,
 until I had caught it,
 and when I thought I had got it I was not satisfied until I had repeated it over and over,
 until I had put it in language plain enough as I thought for any boy I knew to comprehend.
 This was a kind of passion with me,
 and it has since stuck by me.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A passion?
 Yes,
 it must have amounted to that,
 for Mentor Graham,
 the schoolmaster of New Salem,
 testified:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I have known Lincoln to study for hours the best way of three to express an idea.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An all too common reason why men fail to be intelligible is this:
 the thing they wish to express is not clear even to themselves.
 Hazy impressions!
 Indistinct,
 vague ideas!
 The result?
 Their minds work no better in a mental fog than a camera does in a physical fog.
 They need to be as disturbed over obscurity and ambiguity as Lincoln was.
 They need to use his methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
APPEAL TO THE SENSE OF SIGHT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nerves that lead from the eye to the brain are,
 as we observed in Chapter IV,
 many times larger than those leading from the ear;
 and science tells us that we give twenty-five times as much attention to eye suggestions as we do to ear suggestions.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

One seeing,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says an old Japanese proverb,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

is better than a hundred times telling about.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So,
 if you wish to be clear,
 picture your points,
 visualize your ideas.
 That was the plan of the late John H.
 Patterson,
 president of the well known National Cash Register Company.
 He wrote an article for System Magazine,
 outlining the methods he used in speaking to his workmen and his sales forces:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I hold that one cannot rely on speech alone to make himself understood or to gain and hold attention.
 A dramatic supplement is needed.
 It is better to supplement whenever possible with pictures which show the right and the wrong way;
 diagrams are more convincing than mere words,
 and pictures are more convincing than diagrams.
 The ideal presentation of a subject is one in which every subdivision is pictured and in which the words are used only to connect them.
 I early found that in dealing with men,
 a picture was worth more than anything I could say.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Little grotesque drawings are wonderfully effective.
 I have a whole system of cartooning or 'chart talks.' A circle with a dollar mark means a piece of money,
 a bag marked with a dollar is a lot of money.
 Many good effects can be had with moon faces.
 Draw a circle,
 put in a few dashes for the eyes,
 nose,
 mouth,
 and ears.
 Twisting these lines gives the expressions.
 The out-of-date man has the corner of his mouth down;
 the chipper,
 up-to-date
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 fellow has the curves up.
 The drawings are homely,
 but the most effective cartoonists are not the men who make the prettiest pictures;
 the thing is to express the idea and the contrast.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The big bag and the little bag of money,
 side by side,
 are the natural heads for the right way as opposed to the wrong way;
 the one brings much money,
 the other little money.
 If you sketch these rapidly as you talk,
 there is no danger of people's letting their minds wander;
 they are bound to look at what you are doing and thus to go with you through the successive stages to the point you want to make.
 And again,
 the funny figures put people in good humor.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I used to employ an artist to hang around in the shops with me and quietly make sketches of things that were not being done right.
 Then the sketches were made into drawings and I called the men together and showed them exactly what they were doing.
 When I heard of the stereopticon I immediately bought one and projected the drawings on the screen,
 which,
 of course,
 made them even more effective than on paper.
 Then came the moving picture.
 I think that I had one of the first machines ever made and now we have a big department with many motion picture films and more than 60,000 colored stereopticon slides.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not every subject or occasion,
 of course,
 lends itself to exhibits and drawings;
 but let us use them when we can.
 They attract attention,
 stimulate interest and often make our meaning doubly clear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
ROCKEFELLER RAKING OFF THE COINS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mr.
 Rockefeller also used the columns of System Magazine to tell how he appealed to the sense of sight to make clear the financial situation of the Colorado Fuel and Iron Company:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I found that they (the employees of the Colorado Fuel and Iron Co.) imagined the Rockefellers had been drawing immense profits from their interests in Colorado;
 no end of people had told them so.
 I explained the exact situation to them.
 I showed them that during the fourteen years in which we had been connected with the Colorado Fuel and Iron Co.,
 it had never paid one cent in dividends upon the common stock.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

At one of our meetings,
 I gave a practical illustration of the finances of the company.
 I put a number of coins on the table.
 I swept off a portion which represented their wages-for the first claim upon the company is the pay roll.
 Then I took away more coins to represent the salaries of the officers,
 and then the remaining coins to represent the fees of the directors.
 There were no coins left for the stockholders.
 And when I asked:
 'Men,
 is it fair,
 in this corporation where we are all partners,
 that three of the partners should get all the earnings,
 be they large or small-all of them-and the fourth nothing?'
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

After the illustration,
 one of the men made a speech for higher wages.
 I asked him,
 'Is it fair for you to want more wages when one of the partners gets nothing?' He admitted that it did not look like a square deal;
 I heard no more about increasing the wages.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Make your eye appeals definite and specific.
 Paint mental pictures that stand out as sharp and clear as a stag's horn silhouetted against the setting sun.
 For example,
 the word 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

dog
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 calls up a more or less definite picture of such an animal-perhaps a cocker spaniel,
 a Scotch terrier,
 a St.
 Bernard,
 or a Pomeranian.
 Notice how much more distinct an image springs into your mind when I say 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

bulldog
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 -the term is less inclusive.
 Doesn't 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

a brindle bulldog
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 call up a still more explicit picture?
 Is it not more vivid to say 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

a black Shetland pony
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 than to talk of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

a horse
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

?
 Doesn't 
\begin_inset ERT
