 & \text{ con-si-der-a-ble }\\
 & \text{ lab-o-ra-to-ry }
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
ERRORS IN ENGLISH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Review.
 As this chapter completes three-fourths of the course,
 you will find that the following sentences review many of the points which have already been taken up in the study of your language.
 Some of them are incorrect and some are not.
 Look them over and give your reason for the decision which you make in each case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Us men will have to settle the matter.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 If you were him,
 I know what you would do.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 It is us who are to blame.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I interviewed three men,
 none of which were satisfactory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The horse who won the Derby sold for two hundred thousand dollars.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nobody knows who he will take.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I seen him.
 Wasn't you there?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 It looks as if there was going to be trouble sure.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Don't lay down now.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 He bored three oil wells and sunk a lot of money,
 but neither of them paid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He is not so prosperous as he once was.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Either of the cars are all right,
 but he don't intend to buy nothing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He has always drunk heavily.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 He had ought to have known better.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Everybody ought to take their own bait and tackle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New Study Material.
 Rule:
 So many people use who when they should say whom in short questions ending or beginning with a preposition.
 Look at the sentences given below and you will find that
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 if you turn them around so that the preposition stands first,
 you will probably not make the mistake.
 Some authorities claim that you should never close a sentence with a preposition.
 This is the better rule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Whom did you ask for?
 or For whom did you ask?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 Who did you ask for?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 Whom are you going to the dinner with?
 or With whom are you going to the dinner?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 Who are you going to the dinner with?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Whenever you have any form of the verb to be,
 the nominative case is used after it instead of the objective case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Who did you say the girl was?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Whom did you say the girl was?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 Do you know who it is that is doing this?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Do you know whom it is that is doing this?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 We are in the habit of putting certain expressions,
 like 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

I am certain,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 etc.,
 into sentences.
 This makes it more difficult to decide whether who or whom should be used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 I am giving you an assistant who,
 I am sure,
 will render satisfactory service.
 (Who is the right word because it is the subject of will render.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 I am giving you an assistant whom,
 I am sure,
 will render satisfactory service.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 He is a man whom,
 I am certain,
 you can place in any position.
 (Here,
 whom is the object of can place,
 therefore it is the correct form.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 He is a man who,
 I am sure,
 you can place in any position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 The president who,
 as you know,
 was to blame,
 has been impeached.
 (The key to this is to drop as you know.
 Who is the subject of was in the clause,
 who was to blame.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 The president whom,
 as you know,
 was to blame,
 has been impeached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 Whoever and whomever are used just the same as who and whom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 I will fight with whoever gives me the best offer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 I will fight with whomever gives me the best offer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Whoever wins will take the gate money.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Whomever wins will take the gate money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 You may fight whomever you desire.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 You may fight whoever you desire.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 When a money order is endorsed to someone other than the payee,
 the post office must pay the amount to whoever brings it to the window if he can identify himself.
 (Whoever is correct here because it is the subject of brings.
 The preposition to has an object but it is the whole clause,
 whoever brings it to the window,
 etc.,
 that is so considered.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indifference-Apathy.
 Indifference expresses absence of feeling toward certain things.
 Apathy is an entire lack of feeling.
 You may be indifferent about an election in your city.
 You are apathetic about the elections in Johnson County,
 Missouri.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likely-Apt-Liable.
 (Wrong) 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

His obstinacy is likely to get him into trouble.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Better say:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

His obstinacy is liable (or apt) to get him into trouble.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Apt suggests a natural tendency;
 as,
 people are apt to blame their misfortunes on Fate.
 Likely refers to a probable and not ur.pleasant contingency;
 as,
 Our horse is likely to win the Bellair Handicap Race.
 Liable suggests something unpleasant;
 as,
 We are liable to have trouble.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Permit-Allow.
 You permit people to cross a field if you approve,
 sanction,
 or authorize the crossing,
 but if you do not attempt to prevent it,
 you allow it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recollect-Remember.
 Remember does not necessarily suggest an effort;
 recollect does.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-DEVELOPING RESONANCE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following discussion of resonance and exercises for its development were written especially for this course by Professor R.
 J.
 Hughes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do you remember,
 when you were a boy,
 how,
 when you stuck your head into the half-empty rain barrel,
 and uttered a sound,
 the wonderful effect produced fairly made your ears ring?
 That effect was due to resonance or sympathetic vibration.
 The sound you produced was magnified many times by being communicated to the air partially inclosed in the upper part of the barrel.
 All musical instruments,
 the drum with its barrel,
 the horn with its tube and bell,
 the piano with its sounding-board,
 the violin with its body of seasoned wood,
 all these are constructed on the principle that a comparatively weak initial sound can be reinforced and multiplied in power by communicaing itself to a suitable elastic medium whether it be air,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 wood,
 or metal.
 The human voice is such a musical instrument.
 The feeble buzzing of the vocal cords is the initial sound which sets in vibration the chest and the partially open air cavities of the pharynx,
 mouth,
 and nose where it is wonderfully re-entorced and gains greatly in power and grandeur.
 If we heard only the initial buzz of the vocal cords,
 a voice would be heard only a few feet away and would have none of the characteristics we associate with human speech.
 The resonance of the chest is largely automatic while that of the cavities of the head is under the control of the will and by skillful use can be made to produce both beautiful and powerful effects.
 A speaker of my acquaintance who used to have a singularly toneless and empty voice has by careful study and faithful practice gained full use of his head resonance and now for some years has been noted for the ringing quality of his voice and for his ability to fill large auditoriums with ease.
 Instruction in the proper use of your resonators,
 especially the mouth and the nose,
 must be an important part of your education as a public speaker.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the vibrating air as it leaves the larynx or voicebox,
 we follow it up through the open throat until it reaches the veil of the soft palate which you can see hanging at the back of the mouth.
 Under its arch a part of the breath stream enters the mouth and another part rises through the passageway back of this veil or curtain into the nose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of these two cavities the nose is the larger and has as irregular and varied a surface as the interior of a rocky cavern.
 Have you ever talked loudly or hallooed in a cave?
 Reverberations such as you never heard before greeted your astonished ears.
 In a similar way brilliant and tich qualities are added to your voice in the queer-shaped cavernous spaces of your nose and head.
 This is called 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

head resonance.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 At the same time the other stream,
 which entered the mouth under the arch of the palate,
 is undergoing an entirely different change.
 Besides being reenforced in volume just as was the stream that entered the nasal cavity by the rear door,
 this second breath stream is modified by the shape given to the interior of the mouth
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 by the plastic tongue and mobile lips.
 These mouth modifications of the feeble initial tone are called vowels.
 Thus we learn that vowels are merely mouth resonances,
 not made at all by the vocal cords.
 At the larynx all vowels are the same.
 The mold temporarily given to the inside of the mouth,
 largely by the tongue,
 determines what vowel shall come out.
 Thus the mouth is the vowel chamber,
 where also the interferences called consonants are made.
 We will now show you how to use the three resonating cavities most effectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chest cavity resounds automatically when you support your tone firmly on your controlled breath,
 as you learned in Chapter V.
 You can feel it when you place your hand upon your upper chest.
 It is stronger on the deeper tones of low pitch;
 but can be felt throughout the speaking range of the adult male voice.
 Support your voice with your deep breath on every word uttered and you will get full aid from your chest resonance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As for your nasal resonance,
 this valuable aid can only be obtained by special training.
 At the very outset we must know the difference between nasal resonance and nasal 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

twang.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

twang
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is produced when the tone does not go through the nose freely.
 Close both your nostrils with thumb and forefinger.
 Now try to say,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The moon is beaming.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Notice the disagreeable nasality.
 Remove the obstruction and you can imitate the effect by voluntarily preventing the tone from going through the nose.
 Now say the sentence by allowing the tone to flow freely through the nose.
 The disagreeable quality has disappeared.
 You must talk with the word pronounced 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

forward
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in the mouth but the tone must pass freely through the nose at the same time.
 Here are some exercises which will help to give you good head-resonance and carrying power.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exercise I.
 Inhale deeply.
 Gradually expel the breath with a soft hissing sound forming the consonants.
 Repeat,
 and while hissing,
 suddenly close the lips without stopping the steady flow of breath which will now pass through the nose,
 making the humming consonant 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exercise 2.
 Inhale deeply.
 Hum 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Then without stopping the hum change it to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 by opening the lips and lifting the tip of the tongue to the hard palate.
 Alternate 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 repeatedly,
 keeping up a continuous stream of resonance,
 sounding like 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

minim,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 repeated continuously.
 Notice where the sensation of vibrating air is felt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exercise 3.
 Vary Exercise 2 by introducing the vowel sound 
\begin_inset Formula $ee$
\end_inset

 between the hums and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

;
 thus,
 menemene,
 etc.
 Notice the clear resonance of the vowel in the front of the mouth-chamber while the hum still continues in the nose without interruption.
 This humming sound during the utterance of the vowel is important.
 Feel it as well as hear it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exercise 4.
 Repeat Exercise 3,
 then without stopping the stream of resonance,
 change ee into ah,
 forming mene ah,
 which will give a clear ringing 
\begin_inset Formula $ah$
\end_inset

 sound heard in the front of the mouth just back of the upper front teeth while the hum must be heard simultaneously in the head cavities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exercise 5.
 Repeat slowly 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

mean,
 mine
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 several times without stopping the stream of resonance in the nasal cavities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
