\end_inset

 Wrong:
 You and 
\begin_inset Formula $me$
\end_inset

 ought to go right now.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 Were you and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 invited?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Were you and me invited?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reticent-Reserved-Taciturn.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $re$
\end_inset

 ticent man keeps his own counsel;
 the reserved man usually is cold and restrained in addition to being reticent;
 the taciturn man is habitually uncommunicative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Select-Choose-Prefer.
 (Wrong) 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

He has no preference,
 so he selected the first one he put his hands on.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Select suggests a careful choice.
 Preference implies a desire.
 Out of regard for his wife,
 a man may choose (not select) the seashore for his vacation,
 when he himself prefers a fortnight in the Canadian woods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Social-Sociable.
 (Wrong) 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

He is a social man.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Social refers to society;
 as,
 social intercourse,
 social questions.
 Sociable means companionable;
 as,
 he is a sociable man.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transpire-Happen.
 Happen means occur;
 transpire means become known.
 A mine disaster might not transpire until hours after it had happened.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unique-Rare.
 Unique means the only one of its kind.
 Rare signifies infrequent.
 Enduring speeches are rare.
 Lincoln's Gettysburg address is unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-NASAL RESONANCE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Theodore Roosevelt,
 during his first political campaign,
 found his voice giving out on him very soon after he started on a strenuous speaking tour.
 He secured a vocal instructor to travel with him on the train;
 and between stations Roosevelt was practising 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

ding-dong,
 sing-song,
 hong-kong,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 accentuating the 
\begin_inset Formula $ng$
\end_inset

 sound,
 making it ring through his nose to develop nasal resonance.
 Nasal resonance gives both brightness and carrying power;
 and is highly desirable when one is speaking at a distance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Practise the exercise that Roosevelt used.
 Then read aloud,
 not once,
 but once a day,
 the following verse from Poe's The Bells.
 I am asking you to read these for the following reasons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Practise it for nasal resonance.
 Let the sound of bells,
 bells,
 bells ring through the cavern of your nose,
 and,
 in fact,
 through all the irregular cavities of your head.
 As we have pointed out in previous chapters,
 breathe in deeply and then try to feel while you are reading and using breath that same open feeling in the head that you experienced when inhaling.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Read this also as an exercise for developing strength and agility in the tip of your tongue.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 sounds,
 so frequent in these verses,
 are almost ideal for that purpose.
 To refresh your mind on this exercise,
 turn to the voice exercise in Chapter VI.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Read these verses as a means of developing the bright,
 happy overtones of your voice.
 (See Voice Exercise,
 Chapter VII.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Read the first verse aloud in a falsetto pitch.
 (See Chapter VII.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
