\begin_layout Section*
ERRORS IN ENGLISH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Review.
 There are three errors in the following paragraph.
 Can you locate them?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Was this done by you,
 or who?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 was the shout exploded at us as we came through the door.
 It was a question of whether he or myself should take the blame.
 He don't feel that the fault was his,
 and I feel that it was not mine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New Study Material.
 Rule:
 Words joined to the subject by such expressions as with,
 together with,
 as well as,
 in addition to,
 do not pluralize the subject and do not cause the subject to require a plural verb.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 The task of getting proper machinery,
 with that of raising capital and of employing experienced hands,
 was enormous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 The task of getting proper machinery,
 with that of raising capital and of employing experienced hands,
 were enormous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 The invoice mailed yesterday,
 in addition to the bills due last month,
 has been paid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 The invoice mailed yesterday,
 in addition to the bills due last month,
 have been paid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Major Harvey,
 as well as Colonel Mills,
 has appraised the property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 Major Harvey,
 as well as Colonel Mills,
 have appraised the property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Our entire factory with all of its contents,
 together with three adjoining storerooms,
 was burned yesterday.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 Our entire factory with all of its contents,
 together with three adjoining storerooms,
 were burned yesterday.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 Do not use the double negative.
 Note the examples which follow:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 I can hardly see.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 I can't hardly see.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 I never cause any harm to anyone.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 I never cause no harm to nobody.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Do not use never to take the place of not.
 Examples of this are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 I did not bring my notebook to take dictation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 I never brought my notebook to 'ake dictation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 In certain sections of the country especially,
 it is customary to misuse yet,
 already,
 once,
 and however.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 The letter is still here.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 The letter is here yet.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 He has gone already.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 He has gone already yet.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 At the beginning of a sentence do not use such introductory words as why,
 well,
 then,
 now,
 see,
 and again,
 unless they are needed.
 They are very often used because the speaker has gotten into such a habit.
 Effective speaking,
 both in public and in conversation,
 is often marred by this habit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some contracted forms cause trouble in speaking.
 The most important of these are don't,
 doesn't,
 hain't,
 ain't.
 Don't is a contraction of do not,
 and therefore should be used with plural subjects and with 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 You may say 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 don't,
 we don't,
 you don't,
 they don't,
 and don't with any other plural subject,
 but you should never say he don't,
 she don't,
 it don't.
 Examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 He does not care for the theater.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 He don't care for the theater.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Hain't is a provincialism and is used very extensively in certain sections of the United States.
 If possible,
 it is more erroneous than ain't.
 Both of these expressions are improper contractions for are not,
 aren't,
 have not,
 haven't,
 has not,
 hasn't,
 is not,
 isn't.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 Isn't he here?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wong:
 Ain't he here?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 Haven't you got it?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Hain't (or ain't) you got it?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Bent-Bias-Inclination-Prepossession.
 These words agree in describing a permanent influence upon the mind which tends to decide its actions.
 Bent denotes a fixed tendency of the mind in a given direction.
 It is the widest of these terms and applies to the will,
 the intellect and the affections taken conjointly;
 as,
 the whole bent of his character was toward evil practices.
 Bias is literally a weight fixed on one side of a ball used in bowling and causing it to swerve from a straight course.
 Used figuratively,
 bias applies particularly to the judgment,
 and denotes something that acts with a permanent force on the character through that faculty;
 as,
 the bias of early education,
 early habits,
 etc.
 Inclination is an excited state of desire or appetency;
 as,
 a strong inclination to the study of law.
 Prepossession is a mingled state of feeling and opinion in respect to some person or subject which has laid hold of and occupied the mind previous to inquiry.
 The word is commonly used in a good sense,
 an unfavorable impression of this kind being denominated a prejudice.
 'Strong minds will be strongly bent,
 and usually labour under a strong bias;
 but there is no mind so weak and powerless as not to have its inclinations,
 and
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 none so guarded to be without its prepossessions.'–Crabb.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Webster's International Dictionary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Enormous-Immense-Excessive.
 Ehormous means out of due proportion,
 beyond the normal.
 A prize fighter has enormous strength.
 Immense denotes a very iarge quantity,
 a vast extent.
 Excessive means beyond what is just,
 and always denotes something evil.
 The Aquitania is an enormous ship sailing across an immense expanse of sea.
 If a person of moderate means were obliged to pay for one of its de luwe suites he would undoubtedly consider the price enormous,
 probably excessive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-HOW TO BE HEARD AT A DISTANCE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not necessary to shout and yell in order to make yourself heard in a large hall or out of doors.
 It is necessary only to use your voice correctly.
 A whisper,
 if reënforced by the right tone conditions,
 will carry to the farthest corner of the largest theater.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are some suggestions that will aid you in being heard.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I.
 Do not gaze at the floor,
 That is amateurish.
 It is annoying to an audience.
 It destroys a sense of communication,
 a feeling of give and take,
 between the listeners and talker.
 It also directs the tone toward the floor and interferes with its floating out over the audience.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The breath,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 said Madame Schumann-Heink.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

is the motive power of voice.
 Without it under
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 intelligent control,
 nothing can be accomplished.
 One might as well try to run an automobile without gasoline as to sing without breath.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Yes,
 or to speak without it.
 It is the powder behind the bullets of your words.
 There should be,
 at all times,
 a reserve of breath in your lungs to act as a spring board,
 a catapult,
 to launch your words.
 You have doubtlessly seen,
 in store windows or in shooting galleries,
 little balls dancing up and down,
 on jets of water.
 Your words should be buoyed up by breath like that.
 They should ride like a kite on a cushion of air.
 So breathe deeply,
 feeling the lower part of the lungs expanding at the lower ribs and pushing down and flattening out the arched diaphragm.
 When you start to speak,
 do not use up all your breath at once.
 Use as little as possible.
 Control it according to the directions given in Chapter V.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3.
 Relax the throat,
 the lips,
 the jaw.
 (See Chapters IV,
 IX and X.) Constricted tones will not carry because they have little vibration.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 4.
 A man pounding with a hammer on a piece of iron will make a disagreeable noise which is all but deafening close at hand;
 but it will not carry.
 But the music of an orchestra or a band can be heard playing for a long distance through a racket and uproar.
 Why the difference?
 That is easy to explain:
 the instruments of the band make pure,
 harmonious sounds,
 sounds with resonance;
 but the hammer striking the iron makes only a dull,
 ugly clangor without resonance.
 Only a few days ago,
 the author stood beside a bugler sounding a call.
 Had the bugler used the same amount of breath
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 in a harsh shout,
 it would not have carried very far;
 but this breath sent into the bugle,
 vibrating in its resonance chambers,
 created sound waves which carried a long,
 long distance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can understand why some voices that seem very loud to those in the front rows,
 do not carry far:
 they lack resonance,
 and it is resonance that makes a sound carry-resonance and openness and breath reserve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So practise often the voice exercises given for this purpose in Chapters IV,
 IX and X.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As you are listening to the radio,
 hum the tunes that are played,
 feeling with your open palm the vibrations in the top and back of your head,
 in the nose,
 on the lips,
 in the cheeks,
 in the chest.
 To make the most of your natural resonance,
 speak with the same open sensation in your head that you have when you are drinking in the air.
 This is most important.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 5.
 Sound your vowels distinctly.
 They are the very heart of your words.
 It is the vibration of the vowel sounds that carries.
 Consequently,
 they must not be neglected or slighted.
 They must be spoken with freedom and openness and accuracy.
 Here are the most commonly used vowel sounds:
 Practise them aloud now :
 māte,
 mōte,
 mūte,
 moot;
 răck,
 rĕck,
 rĭck,
 rŏck,
 rŭck,
 rook;
 bah,
 boil.
 As you say them,
 relax and drop the jaw.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say them again,
 using them this time as an exercise for flexibility of the lips.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The correct use of the lips is all important in the sounding of the vowels.
 The following are sometimes called small or feminine vowels.
 They ex-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 press delicacy.
 The lips should be stuck out almost into a pout as they are pronounced.
 Try them now.
 We have connected these vowel sounds with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to give them a singing quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $en$
\end_inset

 as in men
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 ain as in drain
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 een as in seen
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 in as in sin 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are the bright vowels,
 expressing joy,
 sunshine,
 gladness.
 Say them with the lips drawn back into something like a smiling position:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 an as in can
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 ein as in line
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 ahn as in ah 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{displayquote}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are the heavy or masculine vowels,
 expressing strength,
 sonority,
 richness,
 fulness,
 depth.
 Say them with the lips a little more open than in the whistling position,
 chin relaxed,
 dropped and very loose.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $on$
\end_inset

 as in on
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 ohn as in oh
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $oon$
\end_inset

 as in boon
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $own$
\end_inset

 as in own
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 6.
 The pitch of your voice ought to vary,
 ought to flow up and down the scale,
 naturally and spontaneously as you speak.
 This principle of delivery was discussed in Chapter VII.
 This change of pitch will help to individualize your words,
 to make them more distinctive.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 7.
 In order to be heard at a distance,
 we need
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 volume.
 Do not confuse this with mere loudness.
 A man who does not mean what he says and has slight interest in it,
 will not,
 other things being equal,
 be heard as far as the one who puts his heart and soul and sincerity into his talk.
 It is not emptiness that carries.
 It is richness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the first things that the physician notices on entering the sick room is the voice.
 It reflects one's vitality.
 A robust voice with carrying power does not come from a sick or even tired body.
 So rest before you speak.
 Obey the laws of sensible living.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

A beautiful voice,
 beautifully used,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 warns Madame Melba,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

can only continue to come from a healthy body.
 .
 .
 .
 Robust health is essential tc any large measure of success.
 .
 .
 .
 Plenty of fresh air,
 simple nourishing food and eight or nine hours of sleep are all necessary to the singer whose larynx invariably reflects her bodily conditions.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CHAPTER XV
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 HOW TO GET ACTION
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The truly effective speakers never have enthroned blind impulse as their god.
 They have controlled and directed it with the judgment born of a careful study of the laws governing action and belief.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Effective Speaking,
 by Arthur Edward Phillips.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Every business talk,
 whether it is selling a stove or putting a factory policy up for vote,
 has a definite end to gaina decision to win-a product or an idea to sell.
 It is therefore as much dependent upon an appeal to 'you' interests as a business letter or an advertisement on the billboard across the street.
 The talk that is so planned and directed is as sure to win against unplanned conversation,
 as is the carefully prepared and tested advertisement.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

How To Talk Business to Win.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

What then,
 in brief,
 does a cultivated modern audience demand of a speaker?
 It insists,
 first,
 that the speaker himself be genuine;
 second,
 that he know something worthwhile and know it well;
 third,
 that his own feelings and convictions be fully enlisted in the theme that he presents;
 and,
 fourth,
 that he talk straight to the point in simple,
 natural,
 forceful language.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Public Speaking Today,
 by LockwoodThorpe.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

The great end of life is not knowledge but action.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Huxley.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Action is the distinguishing characteristic of greatness.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 –E.
 St.
 Elmo Lewis.
