\begin_layout Section*
ERRORS IN ENGLISH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Review.
 Read over the following paragraph and note the errors contained in it:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mr.
 Jones,
 as well as two other friends of mine,
 have endorsed the note.
 He,
 with the others,
 have learned of the increased demand for my patented article and feel that money in addition to talent are necessary for the marketing of the machine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New Study Material.
 Rule:
 Always place your adjectives and adverbs so that it is very easy to tell which words they modify.
 There are daily errors in the use of only,
 nearly,
 almost,
 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 I had only one minute to catch the train.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 I only had one minute to catch the train.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Do not use the superlative degree for the comparative.
 If you are comparing but two objects,
 use the comparative degree.
 Examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 This day is the worse of the two.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 This day is the worst of the two.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Do not use these or those before such words as type,
 kind,
 sort.
 Examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 That kind of houses seldom lasts long.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 Those kind of houses seldom last long.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Right:
 We can never get this sort of prices.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 We can never get these sort of prices.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Rule:
 Do not say kind of a,
 sort of a,
 type of a,
 Note the following examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 That kind of job is simply a blind alley.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 That kind of a job is simply a blind alley.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 That sort of employer deserves labor troubles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wrong:
 That sort of an employer deserves labor troubles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right:
 That type of engine is very expensive.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Wrong:
 That type of an engine is very expen-.
 sive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 We are in the habit of using certain superfluous words in some of our expressions.
 You will be able to see for yourself,
 in the following examples the reasons why the right hand column is not correct:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
