\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 There are certain words which are always plural in form but which take the singular verb.
 Among these are:
 physics,
 eíhics,
 mathematics,
 news,
 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 When such words as dozen,
 score,
 yoke,
 have a numeral in front of them,
 no 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is needed,
 as 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

He bought two dozen eggs.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Another use is 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Dozens of men were killed in the charge.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 There are certain foreign words which have retained their own plurals.
 Among these are:
 addendum,
 alumnus,
 alumna (fem.),
 analysis,
 crisis,
 datum,
 erratum,
 parenthesis,
 phenomenon,
 synopsis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These plurals are addenda,
 alumni,
 alumne (fem.),
 analyses,
 crises,
 data,
 errata,
 parentheses,
 phenomena,
 synopses.
 The modern tendency seems to take memorandum out of this class and to make memorandums the new plural.
 You will find,
 however,
 that many persons are accustomed to use memoranda,
 which is perfectly correct as most dictionaries still hold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 When you talk about several pairs,
 it should be so written,
 as 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Five pairs of shoes were sold.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It comes under the same ruling as 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

five years ago.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Both these expressions are correct and the singular form of these nouns should never be used when there is a plural numeral in front of them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rule:
 In compound nouns,
 the important part of the compound receives the mark of the plural,
 as mothers-in-law.
 The mark of possessive will come on the last part of the compound,
 as 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

my mother-in-law's husband.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
CORRECT USAGE OF WORDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A skillful'man has profited both from knowledge and practise,
 as a skillful physician.
 Dexter means pertaining to the right hand.
 Dexterous implies habitual ease and sureness,
 such as we have in our right hands.
 Adroit is very close to dexterous in meaning,
 but it also implies the ability to make quick,
 sure movements,
 either mental or physical.
 Apt means especially qualified,
 but it is not so strong a term as expert.
 Sharp denotes a keen intelligence and a quick,
 nice discrimination.
 The
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 proficient man has gone forward and made considerable progress.
 Competent is often used to indicate the general,
 natural ability that fits one to perform a task.
 Qualified commonly refers to specific training.
 A competent musician might,
 with study and practise,
 qualify for a position with the Philharmonic Orchestra.
 Initiated refers to instructions in the beginnings and rudiments.
 It is derived from the same source as the word initial.
 A man who is initiated in the problems of finance may not be qualified to handle the financial affairs of a large corporation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
VOICE EXERCISE-SPEAKING MORE DISTINCTLY
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to a special article in the New York Times,
 one man out of every seven who sought to become officers in our army during the World War was refused a commission because of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

poor articulation,
 lack of voice and imperfect enunciation.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These handicaps are just as prevalent;
 and almost as serious,
 in civil life.
 Aren't you sometimes forced to ask people to repeat in conversation-especially strangers?
 Haven't you been annoyed by listening to some speaker whom you found it difficult,
 at times,
 to understand?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How often even those whom we can understand lack that clear-cut articulation which,
 according to the author of Acres of Diamonds,
 is the charm of speaking.
 How delightful it is to listen to.
 It
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 is generally felt to be an infallible sign of refinement and culture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every man can improve his enunciation and articulation by practise.
 Deaf mutes are trained to use accurately the muscles of their lips and cheeks and tongues.
 As a result,
 they are taught to speak almost as distinctly as many who possess the faculty of hearing.
 Imagine,
 then,
 what such training can do for the average man.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The easiest sounds to begin with are the consonants which are made by closing the lips.
 There are five of them:
 
\begin_inset Formula $p,b,m,w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $wh$
\end_inset

.
 Here are some rules:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Press the lips tightly together for these sounds always.
 Tighter than you are accustomed to do,
 and for a longer time.
 Many people hardly touch the lips together in making 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

;
 are you one of them?
 Exaggerate the sound,
 as if it were doubled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
