\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last sound,
 wh,
 used to be spelled,
 long ago,
 
\begin_inset Formula $hw$
\end_inset

.
 Think of it like that;
 make the sound of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

,
 and then bring the lips together for the 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

,
 and you will have no trouble in making it distinct.
 Many people sound white,
 why,
 what almost like wite,
 wy,
 wat.
 Do you?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Localize the sensation-feel the pressure of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 of moving,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 of big,
 etc.,
 at the very center of your lips,
 in front of the middle teeth.
 Use both lips,
 upper as well as lower.
 Do you use your upper.
 lip now?
 Stand in front of a mirror and see.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And don't be afraid to push the lips slightly outward on these sounds,
 like a little megaphone.
 You cannot make them plainly otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some Exercises for Daily Use:
 Repeat single lipsounds:
 me-me-me-me;
 pep-pep-pep-pep;
 wo-wo-wo.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Try these nonsense sentences:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Mobile millions of amiable men.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Prohibitive problems prepare to appear.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Breezes are blowing big billows about the bay.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Why whisper,
 when warbling will win everywhere?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following consonants are made by touching the tongue to some part of the roof of the mouth:
 
\begin_inset Formula $t,d,th,n,l,sh,z,ch,j,r,k,g$
\end_inset

 (hard),
 ng.
 Tongue consonants enter into nearly all words.
 For convenience we may group these 14 sounds as follows:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 I.
 
\begin_inset Formula $t,d,th,n,ch,j,z$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k,g$
\end_inset

 (hard),
 ng.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 3.
 
\begin_inset Formula $l,s,sh,r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall here consider the first group.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 To make the sounds of 
\begin_inset Formula $t,d,th,n,ch,j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 accurately,
 easily and quickly,
 take pains to press the tongue tightly against the roof of the mouth.
 Most people use their tongues lazily.
 They say 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

cer'nly
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 when they think they are saying 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

certainly
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

;
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

moun'n
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 when they think they are saying 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

mountain.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 That is downright carelessness.
 Make your-
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 self squeeze the tongue tight;
 this alone will go far toward making your speech distinct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make these sounds quickly and easily,
 narrow the tongue to a point like a pencil,
 and use only the tip,
 the first quarter-inch or so;
 don't slap the whole broad surface upward as you say 
\begin_inset Formula $t,d$
\end_inset

,
 etc.
 And touch the roof of the mouth just behind the front teeth,
 not farther back.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hold a mirror before your mouth and repeat these nonsense phrases,
 using your muscles actively,
 as directed;
 or make up other phrases of your own:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tip-toeing daintily down to dine.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Lolita laughing neatly taught the tune.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Cherish jealously the jolly ginger jar.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Caruso's faultless articulation,
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 according to Fucito and Beyer in their book Caruso and the Art of Singing,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

was due to the flexibility of his lips and tongue.
 .
 .
 .
 An excellent exercise for the flexibility of the tongue and lips (and also for the distinct enunciation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 ) is:
 tra,
 tre,
 tro,
 tru;
 and bra,
 bre,
 bri,
 bro,
 bru.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Italian voice teachers train their singers a great deal on 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 With the tip of the tongue on the roof of the mouth,
 lips out,
 chin loose,
 say lul,
 lul,
 lul,
 lul,
 lul,
 lul,
 lul.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $l,n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 are called the singing consonants.
 They should naturally sing,
 but most speakers do not make them sing.
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is very good for practise because it gives one the most head tone.
 We used it in connection with the vowel sounds in the last chapter:
 ain,
 een,
 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
