 So I was invited up on the stand with the town officers.
 I took my seat and let my sword fall on the floor,
 and folded my arms across my breast and waited to be received.
 Napoleon the Fifth!
 Pride goeth before destruction and a fall.
 When I had gotten my seat and all became silent through the hall,
 the chairman of the Selectmen arose and came forward with great dignity to the table,
 and we all supposed he would introduce the Congregational minister,
 who was the only orator in the town,
 and who would
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 give the oration to the returning soldiers.
 But,
 friends,
 you should have seen the surprise that ran over that audience when they discovered that this old farmer was going to deliver that oration himself.
 He had never made a speech in his life before,
 but he fell into the same error that others have fallen into,
 he seemed to think that the office would make him an orator.
 So he had written out a speech and walked up and down the pasture until he had learned it by heart and frightened the cattle,
 and he brought that manusript with him,
 and taking it from his pocket,
 he spread it carefully 
\begin_inset ERT
